<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texarkana Editor Mahaffey Dies, 92  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXARKANA, Texas (AP) -- J.Q. Mahaffey, a retired executive
editor of the Texarkana Gazette who was a conscientious community
editor and mentor to young journalists, has died. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Mahaffey, who died Thursday, was editor of the Gazette for three
decades. He also served on the national boards of the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, the Associated Press Managing
Editors, and as a Pulitzer Prize juror.
</P>
<P>
   But he was best remembered for his personal influence on his
community and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''J.Q. Mahaffey was a great editor and a wonderful person. His
relationship with our family goes back three generations,'' said
Walter E. Hussman Jr., publisher of the Texarkana Gazette and
president and chief executive officer of WEHCO Media.
</P>
<P>
   Wick Temple, vice president and director of membership for The
Associated Press, said, ''J.Q. was one of the last of a breed of
newspaper editors who was the conscience as well as the chronicler
of his community, and whose influence stretched beyond Texarkana to
national journalism circles.
</P>
<P>
   ''For many of us, he was a mentor who sent us off into the world
with a reminder that it is not only what one accomplishes that
counts, but the kindness and good humor with which it is done,''
said Temple, who began his career as a teen-ager under Mahaffey's
wing after the death of his own father, an AP newsman.
</P>
<P>
   Louis ''Swampy'' Graves, editor emeritus of the Nashville (Ark.)
News, who worked as city editor under Mahaffey, said, ''J.Q. was
everybody's idol. Those who worked under his tutelage remembered
his patience with young reporters -- and his expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Blocker, retired managing editor the Herald Democrat in
Sherman, Texas, said he was ''floating,'' unsure of what he would
make his life's work, when he started to work for Mahaffey in 1938.
''He helped me peg down what I wanted to do,'' Blocker said. ''J.Q.
was the pivotal point in my young life.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a tremendous force for the community,'' said State
District Judge Bill Peek, who worked for Mahaffey as a young
journalist, and called him one of the greatest influences in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Mahaffey, the son of a prominent Texarkana lawyer, began his own
journalism career at the Gazette after graduation from Furman
University in 1929. He struggled with a stammer, and said humorist
Will Rogers gave him advice about it during a news interview that
kept him from giving up reporting. Mahaffey later became a popular
public speaker known for his humor and storytelling ability.
</P>
<P>
   In four decades at the newspaper, he held almost every editorial
position. One of his proudest accomplishments was bringing women
into the newsroom to cover more than society news. After his
retirement in 1968, he returned to write a popular weekly column
for the newspaper from the early 1980s to the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the honors of his long career was being named editor of
the year in Texas by Sigma Delta Chi, the national journalistic
fraternity now known as the Society of Professional Journalists.
The Baptist General Convention of Texas recognized him for
Christian service in the field of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Mahaffey was born on Oct. 12, 1907. He married Ruth Burgadine in
1935. She died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include a son, John Mahaffey, a retired broadcast news
anchor in Baton Rouge, La., and a daughter, Prudence Mahaffey
Mackintosh, a writer, who lives in Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 0012 </TRAILER>
