<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firework Production Halted in China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A southern Chinese province has ordered factories
that make fireworks and cigarette lighters to suspend operations
and some to close permanently after an explosion that killed 36
people, a municipal official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Another 160 people were injured in the blast Friday at a
fireworks factory in Jiangmen, in Guangdong province. More than 30
people remained missing after the explosion, which leveled the
31,000-square-foot factory.
</P>
<P>
   Guangdong, which borders Hong Kong, has numerous factories and
small workshops making fireworks and disposable lighters. They have
suffered a string of deadly fires blamed on inadequate equipment
and safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
   According to China's official Xinhua News Agency, managers of
the Jiangmen factory ignored an April 4 order from fire officials
to improve their alarm and firefighting systems.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency order issued Saturday by Guangdong province allows
factories that pass a safety inspection to reopen, said an official
of the Jiangmen city propaganda office who gave her name only as
Huang. But those in densely populated areas will be closed
permanently, Huang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
