<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Assured of No Independence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's new president has assuaged the
fears of those in the military that he will declare independence
and bring about war with mainland China, Taiwan's defense chief
said in an interview published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   President Chen Shui-bian has toned down his former
pro-independence leanings, and his conciliatory stance toward China
''has brought peace to the hearts'' of those in the military, Wu
Shih-wen told the China Times, a respected daily.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has said he will abide by Taiwan's constitution -- which
does not support a formal break from China.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan have been governed separately since splitting
amid civil war in 1949, and China has grown increasingly impatient
about reunification with the island. China has threatened war if
Taiwan ever sought to declare independence. Beijing deeply
distrusts Chen because of his former pro-independence tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Taiwan's recently-purchased Patriot missiles and early
warning systems were ''an important deterrent,'' to war, Wu said,
the weapons have their own limitations and there is still a need to
increase defense spending and bolster military training.
</P>
<P>
   China's growing arsenal of Russian-made planes and advanced
missiles are ''a great threat'' to national security, Wu added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 0152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000702.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Early Election in Australia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Australia Prime Minister John Howard
said Sunday he would not try to capitalize on Olympics euphoria by
calling a general election shortly after the Sydney games this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have always thought it a huge political error to believe
that great public festivals like that have any political impact at
all,'' Howard told Australian television's Ten Network. ''I don't
get fooled by that. I won't be doing that, I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister does not have to call an election until early
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Howard also said he had no plans to announce his retirement from
politics. Some political observers have speculated that no
political challenge is left for Howard following Saturday's
introduction of a huge overhaul of Australia's taxation system. But
he denied that he was ready to leave his job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody should think that I'm not enjoying it and that I don't
look forward to doing quite a number of other things before I
depart the political scene.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the first day of Australia's fiscal year, wholesale
taxes were scrapped and replaced by a 10 percent goods and services
levy, while the government also cut income tax by $7.2 billion and
raised child care benefits and pensions for the elderly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
