Israel Complains to UN Over Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel has complained to United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan that Lebanon has not fulfilled its part of a U.N. resolution
outlining an Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, a spokesman said Saturday.
The Israeli delegation to the United Nations sent a letter to Annan complaining
that the Lebanese army had not deployed in south Lebanon since Israel's May 24
withdrawal, Foreign Ministry spokesman Aviv Shiron said. In addition, Lebanese
authorities are located on Israel's side of the border in some places, Shiron
added. The United Nations approval of the withdrawal on June 16 was held up over
Lebanese complaints that Israeli troops were still located in Lebanese
territory.
