<HEADLINE> Jill Sobule Writes About Environment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- What makes urban-angst folk singer Jill Sobule a
good songwriter?
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a voyeur,'' Sobule says in Sunday's Daily News. ''As a
child I was shy and alone. I'd act like 'Harriet the Spy' -- more an
observer than a partaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobule, whose 1995 homoerotic song ''I Kissed a Girl'' was
banned on several Southern radio stations, draws heavily on
real-life characters in her adopted hometown of New York City,
where she has lived for the past 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''You write about your environment. It's no surprise my audience
is East Coast and urban. My records aren't exactly selling in
Bloomington.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I grew up in a Jewish family that was agnostic Jewish. There
was no talk of God,'' she adds. ''In fact, there was disdain for
(religion).''
</P>
<P>
   But she isn't lacking faith, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a running theme of disappointment in my work,''
Sobule says. ''But in the end, I'm like Charlie Brown. I'll go for
that football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
