<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Net2Phone, where NJ politics and high-tech investments meet  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - It's the high-tech choice of high-profile New
Jersey political figures.
</P>
<P>
   A former congressman is president of its parent company. New
Jersey's leading GOP fund-raiser is its chairman. One of New
Jersey's senators participated in an initial public offering of its
stock.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the House made several thousand dollars buying and
selling shares last year. A member of the governor's cabinet went
to work for it after resigning from the administration. The
governor's husband is an investor.
</P>
<P>
   These New Jersey politicians are investing their money, even
their careers, in Hackensack-based Net2Phone Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A majority-owned subsidiary of IDT Corp. of Newark, Net2Phone is
a leading competitor in the cutting-edge field of voice-enhanced
Internet communications. Net2Phone routes telephone calls via the
Internet and says users can save up to 95 percent off international
phone rates.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Net2Phone is Clifford Sobel, finance chairman
for the New Jersey Republican Party and head of fund raising in New
Jersey for Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush. He is
a top fund-raiser for Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's husband, John, held $5,000 to $25,000 in Net2Phone
shares at the time of the governor's May 2000 financial disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, earned $16,000 to $65,000 last
year selling shares of Net2Phone, according to his recently
released financial disclosure form.
</P>
<P>
   Gualberto ''Gil'' Medina, who served as Whitman's commerce
commissioner, left the administration last month to become a vice
president at Net2Phone.
</P>
<P>
   Net2Phone is a subsidiary of IDT Corp., a Newark-based
international telecommunications company and Internet service
provider. Former Rep. Jim Courter, who served in the House for 12
years before running unsuccessfully for governor, joined IDT as
president in 1996. He also is vice chairman of IDT's governing
board and a major shareholder in Net2Phone.
</P>
<P>
   Among those elected this year to IDT's board of directors was
former Massachusetts Gov. William Weld. In 1998, IDT named former
Rep. Jack Kemp, the GOP candidate for vice president in 1996, as
senior strategic adviser to its board.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Purpuro, a former top aide to Courter, was director of
international sales for IDT Corp. until last June, when Republican
National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson appointed him deputy
chief of staff of the RNC.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after Purpuro arrived, the RNC announced it would
begin to accept phone calls to GOP headquarters via the Internet
through a deal with - who else? - Net2Phone.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of New Jersey's most prominent Democrats, Sen. Robert
Torricelli, got it on the act. He took part in an initial public
offering of Net2Phone stock last summer.
</P>
<P>
   According to his financial disclosure forms, Torricelli bought
$15,000 to $50,000 in shares of Net2Phone last July, sold $15,000
to $50,000 in shares two weeks later, and sold another $15,000 to
$50,000 worth three weeks after that. There is no way to tell from
the forms how much money, if any, Torricelli made on the
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey politicians are not the only high-power entities
expressing interest in the two companies. Liberty Media, an
investment arm of AT&AMP;T Corp., bought a 10 percent stake this spring
in IDT. World Wide Web pioneer Yahoo! Inc. bought a 5 percent
interest in Net2Phone in March.
</P>
<P>
   If politicians seem particularly taken with Net2Phone, the
feeling is mutual. Net2Phone is involved in a movement lobbying
Congress not to regulate or tax Internet communications.
</P>
<P>
   The company was a sponsor of an ''Internet Freedom Rally'' last
month in Washington. The rally protested a bill in Congress that
ensures people will never pay per-minute fees to get online. The
bill does not rule out access fees charged to companies, like
Net2Phone and its peers, that provide Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the bill in May, acting largely in response
to rumors on the Internet about a nonexistent bill that would
impose a per-minute access charge on Internet service providers,
ultimately to be passed on to consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-02-00 1330 </TRAILER>
