<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Rescue Death, 1st Ld-Writethru,220  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ISLAND BEACH STATE PARK, N.J. (AP) - A Plainsboro man died after
he tried to help rescue two girls swept off a sandbar by a riptide,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin House, 47, suffered an apparent heart attack Saturday when
he tried to assist another man who had gone after the girls, whose
ages were estimated at 10 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Park Chief Ranger James Hanebury told The Star-Ledger of Newark
the girls were about 100 yards from the beach when a riptide swept
them off the sandbar and into deep water about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' mother, who was on the beach, enlisted the aid of a
park patron, Thomas Wingler of Toms River, who went into the water
to rescue the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Wingler, also in his 40s, was able to reach the girls and help
them keep their heads above water, Hanebury said. However, Wingler
began to tire, and House, who saw the three in the water
struggling, went in the water to help.
</P>
<P>
   House was stricken just as he reached the three. Hanebury said
two other men from the beach were able to pull House, Wingler and
the girls ashore. Efforts on the beach to resuscitate House were
initiated, but he was pronounced dead en route to Community Medical
Center in nearby Toms River.
</P>
<P>
   Hanebury said the state park's eight-mile stretch of beach is
not covered by lifeguards. Beachgoers swim at their own risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
