<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two years after 11-year-old girl killed, suspect's trial looms  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DANIELSON, Conn. (AP) - Two years after an 11-year-old girl was
murdered while delivering newspapers, the man accused in her
slaying nears trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the wait has been a long one for the mother of Angelica
Padilla, whose body was found Aug. 13, 1998 near the Willimantic
complex where she - and, police say, her attacker - lived.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the waiting ... and knowing that I'm going to have to
relive this all over again (during the trial), it's been very
stressful,'' said Mille Mercado, Padilla's mother. ''My life is not
the same and it will never be the same again. My daughter was my
only child, my company, my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime tore through the community. When word spread that
police were closing in on Jose Torres, a crowd about 500 people
strong gathered in front of his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla's murder also touched off debate surrounding Megan's
Law, named for a girl killed by a sex offender who lived in her New
Jersey neighborhood. The law requires convicted sex offenders to
register with police in files that must be open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation, police temporarily kept the sex
offender list from the public, prompting questions and criticism
from parents.
</P>
<P>
   Torres was convicted of third-degree sexual assault in 1996
regarding an attack on his ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Torres beat Padilla to death with a mechanic's
tool in a laundry room of the apartment complex. The girl's throat
was slashed.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 28, has pleaded innocent to charges of capital felony
and murder. He is due in court Friday for a hearing, but his trial
is not expected to begin until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, he could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado said she visits a memorial to Padilla - erected at a
park on Route 195- a few times a week and is buoyed by the
continuing support from the people of Willimantic.
</P>
<P>
   ''People still leave little gifts and prayer cards,'' she said.
''Obviously the community hasn't forgotten and that's helped me so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercado said before going to bed every night, she talks to her
daughter's cremated remains, enclosed in a glass case in her living
room.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst part is at night when Angelica is not here to kiss
me goodnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
