<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groups Want Egypt Professor Freed  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Human rights organizations urged Egyptian
authorities Sunday to release a leading liberal sociologist,
calling his arrest ''a kind of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Saad Eddin Ibrahim, a sociology professor at the American
University in Cairo and head of an Egyptian think tank, was
detained Friday night with three of his assistants and later
ordered detained for 15 days and transferred Cairo's Liman Tora
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim, who holds dual U.S.- Egyptian citizenship, said
prosecutors have charged him with preparing a documentary about
elections that harms Egypt's image, receiving foreign funds without
government permission and forging an election ballot. He said the
ballot was a dummy made expressly for the film.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian Organization for Human Rights said in a statement
Sunday that the arrests are ''generally connected to the state's
desire to silence all establishments that are trying to participate
in the country's public life.''
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group ''has strong suspicions that the state is
practicing a kind of terrorism against civil societies to ... stop
their initiatives in the field of defending human rights or
supporting democracy, or participating in economic, social and
political development.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo-based Arab Organization for Human Rights called for
Ibrahim's immediate release, saying it fears his imprisonment is
related to his ideas and work.
</P>
<P>
   While Egyptian authorities often detain rights activists, it is
rare that an academic of Ibrahim's standing is arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet-spoken champion of human rights, Ibrahim runs the Ibn
Khaldun Center for Development Studies, a Cairo think tank, and is
often interviewed and quoted by foreign journalists. He is also on
the board of directors of the Al Ahram Center for Political and
Strategic Studies, a government-funded think tank.
</P>
<P>
   For years Ibrahim has criticized Arab governments for their lack
of democracy and discrimination against minorities. In Egypt, he
called for greater opportunities for the country's Coptic
Christians, who make up about 10 percent of the country's 64
million people.
</P>
<P>
   The EOHR identified two of the assistants arrested with Ibrahim
as Nadia Abdel-Nour, a Sudanese citizen, and Osama Hammad. The
statement said the prosecution has ordered the arrest of three
other employees at the center, identified as Khaled Fayyad, Mamdouh
Mansour and Ayman Gabal.
</P>
<P>
   The EOHR said such arrests will frustrate active forces in the
society and called on ''all democratic forces in Egypt and around
the world to declare their solidarity with the Ibn Khaldun Center
in defense of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Ibn Khaldun Center: http://www.ibnkhaldun.org/
</P>
<P>
   Egypt Organization for Human Rights: http://www.eohr.org.eg/
</P>
</TEXT>
