<HEADLINE> Cops Tear Gas Macau Protesters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAU (AP) -- Police hurled tear gas canisters Sunday at about
200 unemployed people protesting the hiring of foreign workers on
the island that was recently reverted to Chinese control.
</P>
<P>
   The violence flared when the protesters tried to break through a
police barrier during a march to a park near government
headquarters. The demonstrators, carrying placards and chanting
slogans, threw bamboo poles and rocks at the baton-brandishing
police.
</P>
<P>
   Police warned the protesters to disperse before resorting to
tear gas. The pandemonium sent people fleeing. Police said there
were no reports of injuries and that they detained 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was organized by the Macau Unemployed Workers
Self-Help Association.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a protester was injured during a similar protest.
</P>
<P>
   Macau, with a population of 450,000, employs about 27,000
foreign workers. Many of them come from the Philippines, Thailand
and the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny territory, a popular gambling resort, was hit hard
during the Asian financial crisis and unemployment has shot up.
</P>
<P>
   Macau was returned to Chinese sovereignty last December after
more than four centuries of Portuguese administration. In recent
years, its image has been tarnished by violent gang wars, though
mob killings have tapered off since China resumed control.
</P>
</TEXT>
