<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall seeking to cement one key core of supporters  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Democratic state Comptroller H. Carl McCall
may not be the drunk-with-ambition candidate for governor that
those close to the current governor, Republican George Pataki, are
working hard to portray him as.
</P>
<P>
   But McCall is doing many of the things candidates tend to do two
years or so out from a gubernatorial election they look likely to
jump into.
</P>
<P>
   That includes making sure those groups they count on to form
their core support stay healthy, happy and loyal.
</P>
<P>
   Thus came a letter from McCall personally addressed to some
260,000 of New York's local and state government retirees last week
informing them of what most already knew - that the state
Legislature and governor agreed in June to allow the retirees to
share in more of the assets of the public employees' pension funds
in New York. Perhaps just as important to pensioners, the state
will institute a recurring system of annual cost-of-living
increases.
</P>
<P>
   For an 82-year-old school custodian who retired in 1980, for
instance, the benefit increases taking effect on Sept. 30, 2000,
will increase his annual pension from $5,737 to $7,439. A
60-year-old teacher who retired in 1990 will see her benefits
increase from $30,210 a year to $32,196.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been fighting for this since I took office seven years
ago, but it's the retirees who deserve all the credit,'' McCall
told beneficiaries under the letterhead of the largest pension fund
he administers as comptroller, the New York State and Local
Retirement Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congratulations on finally winning the good fight,'' the
letter continued. ''I am proud to have been with you during this
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall added that retirees could expect another letter from him
this fall providing specifics of how the changes would affect their
individual pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Is this campaign material in the guise of an informational
letter to members of pension funds McCall administers?
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller's aides insisted it was not.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is not a declared candidate for anything, No. 1,'' his
chief spokesman Steven Greenberg said. ''Two, he is in the second
year of a four-year term. Third, and most importantly, this is an
important benefit change affecting 260,000 people and historically
the pension system has always written to retirees to inform them
about changes in their retirement system.''
</P>
<P>
   As sole administrator of the $127 billion pension fund, McCall
would be negligent to his fiduciary responsibilities if he did not
inform retirees about changes in their benefits, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement system paid for the mailing, Greenberg said. He
did not know how much it cost.
</P>
<P>
   Public government retirees are a solid little voting bloc in New
York and of an age - retirement age - where people tend to get to
the ballot box in large numbers on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has proven popular among retirees because he has
advocated for an automatic cost-of-living increase in their
benefits since he became comptroller. Of the 260,000 or so living
retirees from the State and Local Retirement Systems, the vast
majority continue to live in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   But their numbers would hardly be enough to swing most
elections, especially considering Pataki outdistanced his closest
challenger by more than 1 million votes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki is sure to counter McCall's influence among the
retirees by pointing out that as governor he also favored the
cost-of-living increase and was the guiding force behind the STAR
property tax-cut program, which was put into effect for senior
citizens before other homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   These are the calculations made when the sparring starts against
a perceived political opponent, even if the election is 28 months
away.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides have already started to give the scripted answer
when McCall criticizes a Pataki administration agency or budget
that it is ''sad'' the Democratic comptroller is putting personal
ambition above those served by whatever program or department he is
authorized by the state constitution to examine. Often, McCall's
auditors find such mundane problems - frequently, bad computer
software or office bookkeeping practices - that it defies
explanation how his office's criticisms amounts to political
opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon declined to comment on McCall's
letter to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at history, one could wonder why Pataki would feel
threatened by a possible challenge from a state comptroller. No
sitting comptroller won election as governor throughout the 20th
century, and polls consistently show average New Yorkers have only
a vague idea of who their comptroller is or what he does.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki and his advisers can count, too. In 1998, McCall got
more than 2.8 million votes as he won re-election - or almost
300,000 more than Pataki received.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press. He
can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station, Albany, N.Y.,
12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
