<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retransmitting to fix category code  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Julie, the ex-admissions officer, lives in
Thailand, and Lian, the screenplay-writing housewife, in
California. Monica does medical research in Oregon, Sheila is a New
York school principal and sports marketer Liz goes back and forth
between those two places.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Dolan sisters, five women who grew up in Connecticut
but have since spread far and wide. They have different lives and
careers, but share one thing - they love to talk to each other
about everything and anything, from politics to personal health.
</P>
<P>
   Such chats used to be private. No more. Now, the Dolans have
their own radio show, ''Satellite Sisters,'' that connects them via
satellite from their local stations to do what they call
''conversation radio.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We were really trying to replicate the kind of phone calls
that we had with each other, the kind of really encouraging
conversation that used to always make me feel better,'' Julie, 44,
said of the first 12 shows the sisters taped.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite Sisters, co-produced by WNYC Radio, debuted on public
radio April 1 and has been airing in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago
and Portland, Ore., and on the Internet. Now the show is being
syndicated nationally by Public Radio International.
</P>
<P>
   It seems an unlikely endeavor for five women with no background
in radio.
</P>
<P>
   The idea surfaced in 1996 when Liz, then vice president of
marketing for Nike, and Julie, an admissions officer with a
California college, were complaining about their jobs. Listening
in, Julie's husband suggested they find a project for all five
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of dawned on us, the only thing we really know how to
do together is talk to each other,'' Liz, 42, said during a recent
trip to New York that brought together all five sisters for the
first time in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   The other sisters agreed to take part, and the five put together
a proposal that Liz described as ''radio that sounded more like
real life and real conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   She took it to WNYC, the nation's largest public radio station,
where she had contacts. It was good timing because the station
wanted to add more women's voices.
</P>
<P>
   WNYC definitely got more voices with the very vocal Dolans. In
an interview, the five sisters were constantly talking, sometimes
one over the other, and often breaking into laughter. They went off
on tangents, from makeup to the impact of parent organizations in
school.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of freewheeling, silly-to-serious-and-back-again
interaction that the sisters try to capture on air. Topics so far
have included Julie's move to Bangkok for her husband's career and
whether she should pack her gravy boat, how to do proper breast
self-exams - after Lian thought she had found a lump - and the
appeal of a nude juice bar, with comments from a male friend of
Lian.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters often bring in friends or colleagues with knowledge
of certain issues; potential topics are discussed in e-mails and
conference calls with the producers. Julie said the show has an
emphasis on health care and finances because ''we don't think
people, women in particular,'' talk about these enough.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Liz and Julie share anchoring duties with 35-year-old
Lian. Sheila, 41, and Monica, 40, usually contribute segments but
aren't on every show. Each show is expected to feature at least
three of sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the family - the Dolans have three brothers - loves
the show. Their parents, now living in Portland, tune in an hour
early to the public radio station to make sure they don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ''One time, I called and they said, 'We can't talk to you,
you're on the air,''' Julie said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters also hear from listeners who say the conversations
sound like their own chats with sisters or close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a lot of people really like the fact that we're
sisters and they kind of latch on to the back-and-forth that we
have,'' Sheila said.
</P>
<P>
   The five sisters say the show has helped them see different
aspects of each other's personalities. ''It's been a very special
family project,'' Lian said.
</P>
<P>
   And has it changed the way they talk to each other?
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it's almost worse,'' Julie said with a laugh. ''Now we'll
have a conversation not related to work and Lian will start to say
something and it's 'Oh, oh, don't tell me, save it for the show!'''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Satellite Sisters: http://www.satellitesisters.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
