<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With perseverance and a little luck, sisters get film to screen  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Five years ago, two sisters set out to write a
screenplay for a feature film based on several short stories by
Joyce Carol Oates. One sister would direct, the other would take a
starring role.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that neither had ever written a screenplay. Or that
Lisanne, the would-be director, had never directed a feature film.
Or that the subject matter of their movie was to cover ground that
was quite dark, including insanity, domestic violence and lives
built around lies.
</P>
<P>
   But, after dozens of script changes, temp jobs, dead ends and
finally, a little luck, ''Getting to Know You'' opened in New York
for a two-week run last week, and will be screened in Los Angeles
and the San Francisco Bay Area in August.
</P>
<P>
   In a very positive review this week, The New York Times film
critic Elvis Mitchell said the movie ''conjures an alluring spell
of mistrust and hope,'' and that the work itself tests the
independent film system ''because it's missing the cramped,
high-concept, low-budget pushiness that makes many small films the
bargain bin equivalent of studio pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how New York natives Lisanne and Tristine Skyler
moved from the kernel of an idea to a critically acclaimed film is
itself the story of independent cinema - from the scramble for cash
and the struggle against compromising ideals, to the necessity of
always keeping an eye on what sells.
</P>
<P>
   And even after the commercial success of independent films in
recent years such as the ''Blair Witch Project,'' the vast majority
of movies made outside the studio system never make it to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard for people to take a chance on something that's
different,'' said Tristine, ''and much easier for them to want to
make something derivative, if that's what has a record of doing
well commercially.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Skylers had become enthralled by three stories in a
short story collection by Oates called ''Heat,'' that the sisters
describe as being about ''women at a crossroads.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories would be linked into a coherent film by placing a
16-year-old girl named Judith, played by Heather Matarazzo, at the
center of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Judith is waiting for a bus in an upstate New York
bus station when she meets an older boy who snares her attention by
telling her the intimate details of the lives of some of their
fellow travelers - though it is never made clear whether the tales
are true or if the boy has invented them.
</P>
<P>
   Lisanne, 30, who has made several documentaries, including ''No
Loans Today,'' a well-received look at a pawnshop in South Central
Los Angeles that aired on PBS in 1996, had never directed a feature
before. Neither she nor Tristine had written a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   What they did have was a naive sense of their chance of
succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew it wasn't going to be easy, but our passion for the
material really carried us through,'' said Lisanne.
</P>
<P>
   And while they were pushed to do a more mainstream film, the
sisters resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want it to be 'Short Cuts,''' said Tristine,
referring to the film based on several short stories by Raymond
Carver. ''We didn't want it to be conventional.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers were eventually able to get financing for their
nontraditional story in a very traditional way: They lined up stars
- independent stars.
</P>
<P>
   Matarazzo, who set the indie film world on its ear with her
performance in ''Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' had agreed to do the
film contingent on whether it got financing back in 1996 after she
read an early version of the script.
</P>
<P>
   And based on the strength of their script and the help of a pair
of producers they were working with, the filmmakers also got
commitments from Bebe Neuwirth, Mary McCormack and Chris Noth, of
''Law and Order,'' and ''Sex and the City'', simply by mailing
scripts to agents.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters also had a tentative commitment from Casey Affleck,
although he had to drop out to do another film.
</P>
<P>
   After years of dead ends in which it seemed the movie wouldn't
get made, the Skylers eventually got financing through
ShadowCatcher, a Seattle-based production company whose founders
had backed the groundbreaking indie film ''Sex, Lies &AMP; Videotape''
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was contingent, however, on substantial script changes.
As a result, the role of a twentysomething looking for love written
for Tristine was reduced from 30 pages in the script to just 12
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting took place in Asbury Park, N.J., over 22 days on a $1
million budget. An abandoned carpet and tile store was transformed
into the film's bus station. The down-on-its-luck seaside town
stood in for a depressed Rust Belt town.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, things got easier. The film premiered at the 1999
Sundance Film Festival, where it received a positive response. It
also played at the Venice Film Festival, where it was purchased for
the Italian market.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, however, didn't get picked up in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Decisions by distributors are based on what's the hook, who's
going to like it, how do we market it,'' said Lisanne. ''People
don't push independent films to promote art, but because they want
to make money.... Distributors couldn't see the angle.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the film fell between recognized genres: woman's film,
mystery movie, art house flick.
</P>
<P>
   So the sisters waited. For two years.
</P>
<P>
   The wait finally ended when New York's Film Forum movie theater
expressed interest this spring - five years after the sisters first
came up with the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like adolescence,'' said Tristine, ''If someone had told
you how hard it was going to be and all the things you'd have to go
through, you might not want to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
