<HEADLINE> Man Nabbed in Cola Contamination  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- A man who reportedly tried to extort
$730,000 from Coca-Cola's German headquarters by placing
contaminated bottles on supermarket shelves was arrested when he
tried to collect the money, authorities said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old suspect faces at least one year in prison if
convicted on the blackmail charge, said Job Tilmann, a spokesman
for the Frankfurt prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The substance added to the bottles, which were placed on store
shelves around Frankfurt between January and June, was not
life-threatening, Tilmann said. All of the bottles were eventually
located by police, he said, adding ''it wasn't very many.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilmann declined to release other details, saying he did not
want to aid potential copycats.
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman at the offices in Essen declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   A Munich couple is currently on trial in Frankfurt for allegedly
trying to extort money from Nestle by poisoning that company's
products between October 1998 and last December.
</P>
<P>
   A 44-year-old man was sentenced to 11 years last September on
similar charges, also involving brands belonging to Nestle.
</P>
</TEXT>
