<HEADLINE> Iran Nixes New Ties With Egypt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iranian-Egyptian communications have
improved considerably, but formal restoration of diplomatic ties is
not imminent, Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Relations are very different from what they were in the past.
However, reports appearing in the media that the two countries will
establish diplomatic relations soon are not accurate,'' state-run
Tehran radio quoted Hamid-Reza Asefi as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Sadeq Hosseini, an adviser to Iran's minister of
culture, had said Saturday that the restoration of ties with Egypt
was imminent after more than 20 years of estrangement. Iranian
Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad Adeli said last week that
restoration of ties would be announced within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Asefi's comments contradicted those statements. And in
Egypt, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa discounted reports that Iran has
agreed to upgrade diplomatic ties to the ambassador level.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not informed about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and his Iranian counterpart,
Mohammad Khatami, spoke by telephone last month -- the first direct
contact between leaders of the two states since Iran's 1979 Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Ties were severed after Egypt's 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
Relations deteriorated further when Egypt gave refuge to the ousted
Iranian shah, who was buried in Cairo in 1980. But the mood began
to improve after Khatami, a political moderate, took office in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Several lingering diplomatic disagreements still divide the
sides. Iran has objected to Egypt's dealings with Israel, and Egypt
has urged Iran to rename a street named after Khaled al-Islambouli,
the Muslim militant army officer who assassinated Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
