<HEADLINE> Urbanization Conference To Meet  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL GEITNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Call it another millennium milestone: Sometime in
the coming year or so, for the first time in human history, most of
the world's population will be living in cities rather than rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   How to cope with the march toward teeming urbanization --
especially in the poorer countries of Asia and Latin America -- is
the focus this week of a global ''conference on the urban future''
organized by Germany as part of its Expo 2000 world's fair.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan joins Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder in opening the three-day Urban 21 conference Tuesday in
Berlin. They will welcome thousands of academics, public officials,
activists, architects and urban planners from more than 100
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The future of mankind lies in the cities,'' Schroeder wrote in
his welcome address.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ways must be found to keep the social and
ecological problems associated with uncontrolled growth from
smothering the advantages metropolises offer as hubs of economic
development, technological innovation and cultural dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   The conference follows up on objectives laid out by two
U.N.-sponsored sessions on urban development: a 1992 conference in
Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and the 1996 Habitat II summit in Istanbul,
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   At the last session, the United Nations acknowledged that
governments can't solve all urban ills -- from homelessness to
pollution to overcrowding -- alone. It invited activists, businesses
and other experts to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Germany, South Africa, Brazil and Singapore have
worked together on organizing regional meetings to share ideas and
promote problem-solving partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Urban 21 is geared toward a ''global specialist public,'' but
delegates also will hear firsthand about the problems of
''mega-cities'' from those who run them. The mayors of two dozen
major cities -- from Beijing and Moscow to Istanbul and Cape Town,
South Africa -- opened their own summit Sunday in Berlin and were to
present their findings to the main conference.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft of the report to be adopted at Urban 21,
the number of city dwellers will double over the next quarter
century to 5 billion, or nearly two-thirds of the human race, up
from 47 percent a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the growth will be in the developing world, especially
Asia. ''It is here, in the exploding cities of some of the poorest
countries of the world, that the central challenge lies,'' the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of Urban 21 is to ''elaborate solutions, visions and
guiding principles'' to meet that challenge in the 21st century,
German Transport, Building and Housing Minister Reinhard Klimmt
wrote in his official invitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 1451 </TRAILER>
