<HEADLINE> Ugandans Reject Multiparty Politics  </HEADLINE>
By HENRY WASSWA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Ugandans have overwhelmingly rejected
multiparty politics in favor of continuing with President Yoweri
Museveni's ''no-party'' system, according to final referendum
results Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Florence Nkurukenda, deputy chairwoman of the Electoral
Commission, said 90.7 percent of voters ballots chose the
''non-party'' system and 9.3 percent opposed it in Thursday's vote.
Officials said 51.1 percent of registered voters, or about 4.8
million, cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ''People of Uganda fulfilled a constitutional requirement to
choose the political system of their choice,'' said Hope Kivengere,
Museveni's spokeswoman. Kivengere said voting was peaceful and
free.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the referendum could not immediately be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Political parties in Uganda are allowed to exist in name only:
They cannot campaign, raise funds or field candidates on party
colors. Party leaders have argued that basic political rights
should never have been restricted when Museveni came to power in
1986 after a five-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional political parties had called for a boycott of the
vote. But it wasn't clear whether the boycott, rainy weather or
simply a lack of interest was responsible for the low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni blames political parties for creating the religious and
ethnic divisions that plunged Uganda into chaos from the mid-1970s
until he assumed power.
</P>
<P>
   Western donors, who contributed $4.5 million to the cost of
holding the referendum, expressed concern Saturday that the results
could lead to a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The group of donors emphasizes the importance of insuring that
the movement system does not evolve into a de facto one-party
state. Experience shows that such development would not be in the
interest of transparent and accountable government in Uganda,''
their statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
