<HEADLINE> Pair suspected in spree of bank holdups  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. - A Trenton woman and a New York man under
surveillance in connection with a near-monthlong spree of bank
robberies were arrested Saturday after authorities followed them to
a Hopewell Township bank and apprehended them after it was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Annie M. Ford, 31, of Trenton and Tim Martin Johnston, 33, of
New York City were arrested Saturday after the 9:30 a.m. robbery at
a First Union bank branch at the Pennington Circle. A third suspect
remains at large, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they believe Johnston is the person caught on
surveillance videotape in the string of robberies that began June
7. Banks in Trenton, Ewing, Lawrence and Burlington City were
robbed in addition to ones in Falls and Middletown townships in
Pennsylvania. Ford is suspected of assisting in many of the
robberies, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   A task force - made up of the FBI and police from the towns in
which the nine banks were robbed - had placed the pair under
surveillance and on Saturday followed them to the First Union bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''They could have gone to the movies or shopping or to the
shore, but instead they robbed a bank,'' FBI Special Agent Jim
Dougherty told The Times of Trenton for Sunday's edition.
</P>
<P>
   Doughtery said authorities were unable to prevent Johnston from
entering the bank but took up positions outside and awaited his
exit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bank was open, and people were trying to go in, and there
we were with our pistols drawn, waving people away,'' Dougherty
told The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the bank, Johnston ordered a teller to fill a plastic bag
with money. He exited the bank and tried to flee after he was
approached by police. Johnston threw the bag of money into the air
and began to run, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made the apprehension in the middle of Pennington Circle,''
Dougherty told The Times. ''The money was flying all over. A good
bit of it was on the road. We recovered all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was arrested in the bank parking lot, waiting in a vehicle,
Dougherty said. The third suspect remains to be identified, but
authorities said that person also was caught on surveillance
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities declined to reveal the amount of cash taken Saturday
but said it was more than $3,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
