<HEADLINE> Mexican Living in U.S. May Win Seat  </HEADLINE>
By BART JONES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- More than three decades after leading the
Mexican student movement that fought for democracy and workers'
rights, Jose Jacques Medina hopes to speak for another potentially
powerful group: Mexicans who now live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, has put Medina of Los
Angeles and Raul Ross of Chicago on the list of candidates for
Mexico's 200 at-large congressional seats, which are allotted
according to parties' vote percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Medina is so far down the list he has no chance of being
elected. But Ross could be elected if the PRD does well. The party
claims it would be the first time a Mexican national living in the
United States is named to Mexico's Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has held
Mexico's presidency since 1929, has made a similar pledge. Eddie
Baron Levy of Los Angeles is on its list Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Just placing U.S. residents on the ballot is a significant
gesture by parties that in the past have often ignored Mexican
expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida, was in a
neck-and-neck race Sunday against Vicente Fox of the center-right
National Action Party. The PRD's Cuahtemoc Cardenas was in third
place in polls.
</P>
<P>
   The 200 proportional representatives join 300 directly elected
representatives in Mexico's Congress.
</P>
<P>
   About ten percent of Mexican adults -- 7 million to 10 million
people -- live in the United States. PRD leaders say the nationals
don't have a voice in Mexico's Congress partly because the PRI has
refused to back laws that would implement voting beyond Mexico's
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition groups say the PRI fears most Mexicans in the United
States would vote against it. Some Mexican nationals cross the
border to vote, but there are only a limited number of ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, now 55 and a community organizer in Los Angeles, says he
didn't seek the nomination. The PRD came to him.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted, though he doesn't relish the idea of commuting to
Mexico every week for the Tuesday through Thursday congressional
sessions. He long ago established himself in the United States,
where he says he fled to escape persecution -- maybe even death -- at
the hands of corrupt Mexican authorities during a crackdown on
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would lose focus of what I have wanted to do here for the 26
years I've been in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, he said, he hates flying.
</P>
<P>
   Medina gained fame as an activist during the movement that
culminated in a huge protest in Tlatelolco square on Oct. 2, 1968.
Police and soldiers opened fire on the students, killing at least
300 protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexican historians consider the shock of the massacre to be
a turning point in Mexican political life, discrediting the
government while sending a few young Mexicans into guerrilla
rebellion and many more into pro-democracy activities.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Medina was arrested and accused of attempting
to kidnap the dean of the National Autonomous University in Mexico
City -- a charge he denies.
</P>
<P>
   He was 28 years old and could have been imprisoned or even
killed if he stayed, he said. He fled to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By 1980 his relationship with his homeland began to thaw; the
Mexican government granted him an amnesty. He has returned there to
organize conferences on emigrants and to visit relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he gained the right to become a U.S. citizen, and
plans to file the papers soon.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, who is a lawyer and an international representative for
the AFL-CIO, says he would continue to bring his ideas for social
justice to the Mexican Congress if he wins the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues he said he would champion are fair wages for
Mexican workers and legal status for Mexican immigrants in the
United States -- a goal that has earned him the enmity of
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
