<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ hospitals starting to feel pinch of growing nurse shortage  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey hospitals are feeling the pinch
of a growing shortage of nurses, especially in specialties such as
critical care, although a recent survey found most hospitals still
have adequate bedside staffing.
</P>
<P>
   However, to keep units properly staffed, many Garden State
hospitals have been forcing nurses to work mandatory overtime,
angering nurses. That, along with major hospital layoffs in the
late 1990s and practices such as floating nurses to unfamiliar
units, is driving many nurses out of the profession.
</P>
<P>
   But under first-in-the-nation legislation passed Thursday,
forced overtime will be prohibited in New Jersey hospitals and
nursing homes except in emergencies. On top of that, experts warn
an aging nursing work force and a sharp decline in new nursing
students, partly due to increased opportunities for women in
higher-paying, less-demanding fields, will leave about 20 percent
of nursing jobs unfilled in New Jersey by 2006 and across the
nation by 2020 - when most baby boomers will be senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're considering it almost a crisis shortage,'' said Carol
Chernack, spokeswoman for the New Jersey State Nurses Association,
which lobbied for the bill along with nursing unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned about patient care quality,'' she said Friday.
''In certain hospitals, on certain units, on certain shifts, it can
be quite unsafe'' for patients.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey Hospital Association survey of members covering the
last half of 1999 found that - in the hospitals responding -
dayshift nurses in the typical medical-surgical unit were caring
for six patients each.
</P>
<P>
   For intensive care units, the ratio was two patients per nurse,
and in step-down units, where patients are still on monitors and
need frequent care, the ratio was four patients per nurse, said
Cathy Cardea, a registered nurse who directs quality initiatives at
the hospital association.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cardea said, ''the majority of hospitals are having
trouble with a shortage,'' especially of critical care, emergency
room and operating room nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will get worse,'' she said, adding, ''If one
patient goes bad, then a one-to-six ratio may not be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   With 60 percent of New Jersey's 80 acute-care hospitals losing
money due to severe cuts in government and insurance company
reimbursements, hospitals don't have the money to expand nursing
staffs, Cardea said, although nursing executives at hospitals with
worse ratios are hoping to use the survey results as ammunition to
increase budgets for nursing staff.
</P>
<P>
   So along with filling staffing holes with RNs from nursing
employment agencies, hospitals resort to forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bad idea, Chernack said.
</P>
<P>
   ''An exhausted nurse working the 15th hour of a double shift
involuntarily is not who you want taking care of you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On evening and graveyard shifts, the shortage is generally
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you go on the floor, you'll see two nurses assigned to 20
patients,'' said Bernie Gerard, a vice president at the Health
Professionals and Allied Employees union.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hospital association survey shows better staffing
levels than what he sees, and that is compounded by putting very
ill patients, who once would have spent days in intensive care, in
units with less staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard expects Gov. Christie Whitman to sign the bill barring
mandatory overtime, and it would take effect a year later, but a
Whitman spokesman said the governor is still reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hospital and state health department officials have
been meeting with nursing groups to seek solutions to the shortage,
partly under a collaboration funded by the Plainsboro-based Robert
Wood Johnson Foundation called ''Colleagues in Caring.'' Hospitals
are becoming more aggressive and innovative in their recruiting
strategies, offering signing bonuses as high as $3,000 and hiring
nurses overseas, but no clear solution is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''All states are experiencing some shortage, but it's not as
critical'' as in New Jersey, which competes with New York and
Philadelphia hospitals that often pay more, said Geri Dickson,
project director for Colleagues in Caring in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Dickson said, the average age of working RNs - as opposed
to the many RNs out of the 110,000 licensed in New Jersey who work
in other fields - is 43, a year older than the national average.
Worse yet, the average age of new nursing school graduates in New
Jersey is about 32, and the number of graduates has been dropping
about 12 percent per year, falling from a peak of 2,372 in 1994 to
1,899 in 1998. Meanwhile, half the faculty at New Jersey nursing
schools hits retirement age in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   While starting salaries in New Jersey are about $40,000 and the
average wage is $22.65 per hour, salaries don't rise much with
increased experience, further discouraging many nurses.
</P>
<P>
   All those factors threaten the quality of nursing staff in New
Jersey, which has eight of the 18 hospitals nationwide designated
by the American Nurses Association as ''magnet hospitals'' for the
skills and experience of their nursing staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have excellent nurses in New Jersey, and I want to
keep it that way,'' Chernack said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-02-00 1531 </TRAILER>
