<HEADLINE> Chechnya Truck Bomb Explodes  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A truck bomb exploded Sunday in front of a
Russian military headquarters in the Chechen town of Urus-Martan,
in what Russian officials said was a suicide bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The driver tried to crash the truck into the headquarters, but
was stopped short. There were no Russian casualties, said Lt. Gen.
Ivan Babichev, a Russian military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Russian soldiers then scattered a group of rebels preparing to
continue the attack on the headquarters building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Babichev said the attack was a propaganda attempt by rebels ''to
create the illusion that there is widespread fighting,'' but he
said that the situation in Chechnya was under control.
</P>
<P>
   Ramzan Akhmadov, a Chechen guerrilla commander, said by
telephone that there were Russian dead, but he did not specify a
number.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides exaggerate the other's losses and understate their
own, and there was no way to immediately sort out the conflicting
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they have all but won the war to
re-establish control over the rebellious region, but rebels
continue to inflict casualties with mines and ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   In Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city, a bomb exploded
Sunday in the attic of a bathhouse where residents and soldiers
were relaxing. Two servicemen and a local woman were wounded, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Three Russian policemen were killed late Saturday when their car
drove over a homemade land mine at the entrance to a shooting range
in the town of Shelkovskaya, 30 miles northeast of the capital
Grozny, Interior Ministry officials said. Responding to a report of
an explosion at the shooting range, police found the three officers
dead, apparently killed by shrapnel from a land mine made out of an
artillery shell.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen fired for two and a half hours on a military headquarters
in the village of Znamenskoye in the Nadterechny region, a lowland
area the Russians captured last year, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from elsewhere in Chechnya are living in a large camp
in the town, and a three-member team of human rights observers from
the Council of Europe is headquartered there.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary police stations in the city of Argun and the village
of Nadterechnaya were also fired on Saturday night, the officials
said. No Russian casualties were reported in those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian troops on Sunday were carrying out what
officials called ''special operations'' in the towns of Valerik and
Urus-Martan, southwest of Grozny, ITAR-Tass reported. It said the
towns were sealed off, and that 15 people were arrested for taking
part in rebel operations.
</P>
<P>
   Troops combed the woods for rebels around Serzhen-Yurt and
Avtury, near the scene of fighting last week that left 13 Russian
soldiers dead, the news agency said. Russian forces also checked
hospitals for wounded rebels, ITAR-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war.
They returned after Chechnya-based Islamic militants raided several
villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after
about 300 people died in apartment bombings the government blames
on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 1541 </TRAILER>
