<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Ex-Communists Seek Gains  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH COLEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) -- Election results trickled in Monday
from Mongolia's parliamentary elections the day before, with the
nation's resurgent ex-communists expecting to make strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials had made no announcements by Monday evening.
But the International Republican Institute, a U.S. group observing
the vote, confirmed that at least two candidates of the Mongolian
People's Revolutionary Party -- the former communists -- had won in
the capital, Ulan Bator.
</P>
<P>
   The party headquarters in the capital was lively early Monday,
and party officials were optimistic they would gain seats in the
76-member parliament. But they said firm results would not be
available until later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Mongolians walked, rode horses and drove jeeps to the
polls to choose between the scandal-plagued reformist government
and the country's former leftist rulers. It was the first
parliamentary race since a democratic coalition won 50 seats in
parliament in 1996. The coalition has since broken up.
</P>
<P>
   The election took place as Mongolia struggles with a rapid
transformation from communism to free-market capitalism. While the
economy is growing strongly, the transition has thrown many into
poverty and unemployment in this central Asian nation wedged
between Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was expected to be strong, but some of the voting did
not go smoothly. First-time voters in some districts complained
that confusion over changes in the national identification card
system had left them without proper documents to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people don't have these documents, especially herders,''
said R. Burmaa, a member of the General Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote was only the third time Mongolia has gone to the
polls to choose a new parliament. A populist movement overthrew
hard-line communism in 1990. The former communists won the 1992
election before losing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the former communists looked set for another
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Boldbaatar, an unemployed 30-year-old voter in Gachuurt, a rural
town outside Ulan Bator, said the current government has made a lot
of mistakes, so he was throwing his support to the People's
Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their platform gives me hope that they won't fail the people
of Mongolia,'' the son of herders said after voting at the village
schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The election comes amid serious political problems in Mongolia.
Over the past four years, three members of parliament have been
jailed in a corruption scandal, a popular Cabinet minister has been
murdered and the country has had four prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The reformers, led by the Mongolian National Democratic Party,
pledge to keep up the pace of change. They have painted the former
communists as a reactionary force intent on turning back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The former communists have declared unequivocal support for both
democracy and free markets, but they say they would take a more
measured approach to privatization. They accuse the present
government of mismanagement and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from Sunday's voting that Mongolian democracy is
still very much a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Shagdarsuren, a 90-year-old Buddhist monk dressed in a bright
yellow robe with purple cuffs, showed up to vote at a station in
Ulan Bator but couldn't read the ballot. Instead of asking for
help, he simply marked the third choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know who it was,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 1545 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
