<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish leaders, elected officials vow pressure on Iran  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Jewish leaders and local elected officials vowed
Sunday to push for sanctions against Iran following the conviction
of 10 Jews there on charges of spying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Iran must pay a price for this,'' said Rep. Eliot Engel,
D-N.Y., at a news conference outside the Iranian Mission to the
United Nations attended by 150 Jewish leaders, elected officials
and protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the United States lifted a ban on U.S.
imports of Iranian rugs, pistachio nuts and caviar. Although the
change had little economic impact on the Middle Easter nation -
which gets most of its revenue from oil exports - it was considered
a symbolic step toward a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are demanding that the U.S. now rescind the concessions
that were made,'' said Malcolm Hoenlein of the Conference of
Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Engel and two other Democratic congressmen from New York City,
Anthony Weiner and Major Owens, pledged to work to reinstate the
trade bans and withdraw other forms of import and agricultural
assistance to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by Abe Foxman, who heads the Anti-Defamation
League; city Comptroller Alan Hevesi; American Jewish Congress
Executive Director Phil Baum; Rabbi Shmuel Blum of Agudath Israel,
an Orthodox Jewish organization; and others.
</P>
<P>
   Also present was a man Hoenlein described as a close relative of
two of the convicted Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The man would not give his name, citing concern for his family,
but said: ''We hoped for fair trial. ... We are very sad and very
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''They didn't do anything wrong. We ask the Iranian
government to release them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't sure if the international pressure would help.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's verdict drew condemnation from Israel, which denied
that the convicted men had been spies, and from President Clinton,
who said he was ''deeply disappointed'' that Iran appeared to have
treated the men unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 Jews - whose professions range from shoe clerk to teacher
- were sentenced by an Iranian judge to prison terms of four to 13
years. The judge acted as both prosecutor and jury, and observers
were banned from the trial. State television also broadcast
confessions from two of the defendants after months in jail.
Critics dismissed the entire process as a sham.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing against these people, except the fact that
they were Jews living in Iran,'' Hoenlein said. ''These were the
rabbis and leaders of a community, guilty of nothing else but that
they organized classes to study Jewish tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoenlein and other officials said they thought international
pressure may have already helped avert death penalty sentences for
the Jews, and could also have a positive impact on the appeals
process. Iranian President Mohammed Khatami has the power to grant
the 10 clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami is viewed as a moderate trying to refashion his
country's image, but the trial of the Jews took place in courts
controlled by Khatami's conservative rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ''If in fact that moderation is real, and if President Khatami
is sincere about what he has said, this is the time he is being put
to the test,'' said Hoenlein. ''If he is serious, then he will take
the appropriate actions and grant them all clemency and free them
all immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
