<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuation Upsets Conservationists  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DASSEN ISLAND, South Africa (AP) -- Conservationists on Sunday
dragged thousands of wriggling penguins from their burrows and
dumped them into cardboard boxes for evacuation in an effort to
rescue the endangered birds from an oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their frantic efforts, it was clear that only a fraction
of the 55,000 African penguins that live on Dassen Island off the
South African coast could be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can move 10,000 birds off in three days, we've done as
much as we can do,'' said Tony Williams, a penguin expert from
Western Cape Nature Conservation. ''It's a no-win situation. We
have taken 2,000 oiled birds off the island already.''
</P>
<P>
   Fencing erected to prevent the penguins from reaching the
oil-polluted sea must be removed in three days to avoid starving
the birds remaining on the island, Williams said. The fences were
put up Friday, two days after the island's coast was hit by oil
leaked from a tanker that sunk June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Uncontaminated birds captured on Dassen Island were to be
shipped or flown to the mainland, trucked about eight hours up the
coast and released to fend for themselves. They are expected to
swim home within about 11 days. Authorities hope that will give
them enough time to clean up the spill.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are to be monitored through a satellite tracking
device during their swim home.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation was going painfully slowly Sunday: Heavy swell
and a lack of suitable boats made it difficult to transport workers
from the mainland. There are also very few roads on the 540
acre-island, making it hard to reach the birds.
</P>
<P>
   The spill coincided with the birds' peak breeding season,
meaning most chicks and eggs will be lost. Rescue efforts
concentrated on the adult birds, which have a higher survival rate.
Distraught volunteers left young, weak birds in their burrows,
saying they were not expected to live longer than two days.
</P>
<P>
   The spill has set the African penguin population back by at
least five years, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The population has declined by 90 percent in the last century.
About 40 percent of the current population, estimated at between
150,000 and 180,000, is at risk from the spill.
</P>
<P>
   Environment Minister Valli Moosa on Wednesday asked the army to
help rescue the birds, but so far, the defense forces have rendered
minimal assistance -- enraging conservation officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I personally think it's a national scandal. I think it's
probably unprecedented that an environmental catastrophe of this
size could have been occurring for a full week already without any
significant intervention of the defense forces,'' said Ian
Macdonald of the World Wide Fund for Nature, which is helping fund
the relocation.
</P>
<P>
   The defense force said its trucks are tied up monitoring a
conflict between taxi and bus operators in Cape Town and that its
helicopters need servicing.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the mainland, authorities said Sunday about 20,000
oil-coated birds had already been captured -- up from 11,000
Saturday. Many of those birds were taken off Robben Island, another
island off the South African coast which was hit by the oil a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitating the oil-coated birds will be a mammoth task -- it
takes two people about an hour to clean each bird. Once cleaned,
the birds need to be hand-fed for up to two months before their
coats again become waterproof so that they can swim in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to accept there is going to be quite a substantial
mortality rate among the oiled birds,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Penguin-tracking site:
http://www.uct.ac.za/depts/stats/adu/oilspill/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 1641 </TRAILER>
