<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Test Conditions Not Actual  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon concedes a crucial test for the
planned national missile defense system is being conducted Friday
under conditions far more favorable than an actual attack would
allow, Time magazine reports.
</P>
<P>
   Crews firing the intercepter from a Pacific atoll will have
thorough knowledge of the launch, origin and power of the target
missile, probably none of which would be available during a real
attack, the magazine says in its issue on newsstands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it quotes the Pentagon's chief weapons tester saying
all attempted intercepts until 2004 will have intercept crews fully
briefed on the ''timing, direction and countermeasures'' employed
by incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There are virtually no unknowns in the procedure, Time reports.
The crew launching the interceptor will even listen in on the
countdown of the warhead's rocket -- intelligence that almost
certainly wouldn't be available if a rogue state launched a
missile.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Coyle, the chief weapons tester, was quoted as saying
such advantages ''place significant limitations'' on the value of
the test. Coyle could not be reached for comment Sunday by The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The current development schedule for the system, which will cost
at least $30 billion, would have tests advanced far enough by 2005
to put its first 20 interceptors in the field. This week's test
will be pivotal to President Clinton's decision, expected this
fall, whether to give a go-ahead for further development.
</P>
<P>
   Under congressional pressure, the administration proposed the
system to protect against attacks from one or several missiles from
smaller, newly armed countries.
</P>
<P>
   Time reported other ways in which the tests are weighted in
favor of success:
</P>
<P>
   --Meant to defend against ''tens'' of incoming warheads, all 19
scheduled tests will target only one.
</P>
<P>
   --Because of safety considerations, the dummy warhead of the
target will not travel as fast as would a hostile attack.
</P>
<P>
   --Friday's Minuteman II target will fly a familiar trajectory,
the same California to Kwajalein Atoll route used in the
interceptor's previous two tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
