<HEADLINE> Solidarity Leader Launches Campaign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Solidarity leader Marian Krzaklewski
kicked off his presidential campaign Sunday by challenging the
popular incumbent about his communist past.
</P>
<P>
   ''When some were joining the communist party right when the
streets were soaked with blood of Polish workers, others were
getting ready to fight for free and independent Poland,''
Krzaklewski said in his hometown of Kolbuszowa, a southern city
where he came to inaugurate the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Krzaklewski, who replaced Lech Walesa as the Solidarity chairman
in 1991, is credited with reuniting Poland's center-right parties
under the Solidarity umbrella and leading them to victory in the
1997 parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   This October, though, he faces an uphill struggle, against
Aleksander Kwasniewski, an ex-communist who defeated Walesa in 1995
and still holds a commanding lead in opinion polls of about 70
percent. Andrzej Olechowski, an economist who has served in both
left- and right-wing governments, comes in a distant second with
about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Krzaklewski, 49, also promised Poles to fight to protect ''our
national interests at a time when we are making a decision about
our place in the European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer specialist won the endorsement of Solidarity
Electoral Action, a disparate bloc grouping Christian, national and
liberal factions.
</P>
<P>
   Krzaklewski will also be running against Walesa, the legendary
founder of Solidarity. Opinion polls show, though, that both
Solidarity leaders can count on less than 5 percent of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Krzaklewski's chances are also dimmed by the government's
rock-bottom approval ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
