<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State attorney general settles franchise fraud case for $1 million  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The state attorney general has obtained
judgments totaling more than $1 million against a family that
allegedly cheated investors in four states by peddling franchises
to sell inferior snacks and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   In what he called the largest franchise fraud case ever brought
by his office, Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said he won a
settlement that keeps Michael J. Glass, his wife and two sons
permanently out of franchise sales.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the Glasses, operating through three companies,
collected up to $50,000 each from dozens of people who were told
they could earn as much as $780,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Glasses collected almost $1 million, Spitzer said, selling
to investors in New York City, on Long Island, in Westchester
County, as well as 19 counties in New Jersey, and in Ohio,
Connecticut and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   All of the investors lost money and two declared bankruptcy
after Glass, 67, failed to develop the business as he had promised,
Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Glass provided only oily potato chips and a line of
flavored water - which stores dropped when the chip bags leaked oil
and the bottle labels peeled off to reveal different beverage
labels.
</P>
<P>
   Glass's two companies - Westcool Snacks and Beverages and
Maricopa Products - were dissolved for failure to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Iglesias, 36, of the Bronx, said he quit a $30,000-a-year
job with Yankee Stadium's ground crew in early 1995 to put
everything he had into one of Glass' franchise routes. Within a few
months he was unable to get products to sell, had no income and
lost his home.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the settlements, filed last week in Manhattan's
State Supreme Court, include a judgment for $936,525 from Glass and
his two companies. Spitzer's office, however, is still trying to
find Glass's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Glass' lawyer, Gerald McMahon, said the settlement is
''much ado about nothing. It's a paper victory. It's meaningless
because he (Glass) has no money. This was not a fraud. This was a
genuine business venture that went south and now he's in
bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also includes $35,000 collected from Glass's two
sons, Joshua, 32, of Ridgefield, Conn.; and Peter, 37, of
Patterson, N.J.; and from Peter Glass' company, Wacky Snacks and
Beverages. That company, too, is now out of business.
</P>
<P>
   A case involving Michael Glass' ex-wife, Adriane, was settled
for $100,000, a deal that McMahon called ''extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the amounts recovered so far will allow investors
to recoup about 10 percent of their investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-02-00 1704 </TRAILER>
