<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas tax cut taking time to seep in  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   As drivers hit Connecticut's roads during the holiday
weekend,
lower prices at the pumps were not everywhere to be found despite a
7-cent reduction in the gasoline tax.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some motorists continued to pay top dollar, while station owners
and managers took advantage of a grace period to sell off
previously purchased supplies of gasoline, which still carry the
32-cent tax that was reduced to a quarter on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But relief is in sight. Prices are expected to drop in a few
days as current gasoline supplies are depleted.
</P>
<P>
   Stations that immediately passed the tax cut to their customers
were rewarded with a steady flow of customers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody has noticed,'' said Tammy Eye, manager of the Citgo
Food Bag on Route 110 in Shelton. ''We've been extremely busy.''
</P>
<P>
   The station was selling regular unleaded for $1.70 a gallon - 7
cents less than the day before, and as much as 15 cents cheaper
than some other stations within two miles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I looked at (the sign) and I said, 'Man, is that right?'''
said Bill Harris of Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   But the 7-cent cutback in the price of gas is not enough to make
much of a difference, some consumers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wont help at all,'' said George Maselli of East Haven. ''It
used to cost me $5 to mow the lawn. Now it costs me $10,'' he said.
''I don't pay attention to gas prices anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Tom McCabe, who was filling up at the Country
Cloverleaf Store at the Killingworth Circle, where regular gas at
the Texaco station remained at $1.88 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The price goes up and down so much, 7 cents is nothing as far
as I'm concerned. Seventy would be a hell of a lot better,'' said
McCabe, who has to pay $50 to fill the 30-gallon tank in his truck.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors from the state Department of Consumer Protection will
be monitoring pump prices for the next four months to make sure
stations are passing the tax cut to customers.
</P>
<P>
   If drivers suspect they're being fleeced at the filling station,
they can call make a toll-free phone call to the consumer
protection hotline at 1-800-842-2649.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
