<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Wash. Monuments Vulnerable  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- High-profile Washington monuments like the
Lincoln Memorial and Vietnam Veterans Memorial are vulnerable to
terrorist attack, a study commissioned by the National Park Service
concluded as it called for a budget boost to upgrade security.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-page study cites several examples of how terrorists
could easily destroy national monuments and cause mayhem similar to
the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''As symbols of America's heritage, they are high-profile
landmarks, not well protected, popular, attract many visitors daily
and require open and easy accessibility,'' says the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes as thousands prepare to celebrate the Fourth of
July holiday this week on the National Mall. A Park Police official
said visitors have no need to be concerned about the holiday
celebration when virtually every officer on the force will be on
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fourth of July is not a problem,'' Lt. John Kmetz said
Sunday. ''We encourage people to come down. We believe it's going
to be safe because it's a full force commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kmetz said the concern lies with a hypothetical midweek
afternoon incident where one officer might be responsible for
covering several areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to do what we can within our resources to address
them, however a long term approach is going to be necessary,''
Kmetz said of recommendations in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The document makes a director correlation between the
vulnerability of the monuments, including the newly refurbished
Washington Monument and Thomas Jefferson Memorial, and funding for
the U.S. Park Police, the law enforcement arm of the park service.
</P>
<P>
   It said an additional one-time expenditure of $3 million would
bring eight of the most popular monuments up to security standards.
</P>
<P>
   It also says many shortcomings involved a lack of manpower and
poor communication equipment assigned to Park Police.
</P>
<P>
   The study was first reported in Sunday editions of The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Langston, head of Park Police, told the Post that while
protection of other government buildings in the city has increased,
that has not happened with the monuments and memorials guarded by
the Park Police.
</P>
<P>
   The Post pointed out that, while neither agency would comment on
Park Police readiness, both the FBI and the U.S. Secret Service
share responsibility for protecting against terrorist acts that
might be directed against any government installation.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce Hoffman, a Washington-based counterterrorism expert
for Rand Corp., a nonprofit public policy institute, said it is a
given that government monuments are potential targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are by very definition national monuments, which means
they're there for the public,'' Hoffman told the Post. ''So no one
can look at them and say they're not vulnerable. Of course they're
vulnerable. But everything is vulnerable. It comes to a point where
you have to accept that we can't have a risk-free society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 1707 </TRAILER>
