<HEADLINE> Red Sox Outfielder Confronts Writer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Red Sox outfielder Carl Everett yelled at Boston
Globe columnist Dan Shaughnessy in the clubhouse before Sunday's
game, upset about a story that appeared in the paper a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard Carl say, 'Who said (Jeff) Frye and I were
fighting?''' Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaughnessy wrote that Everett and Frye got into an ''animated
discussion'' in the eighth inning of Friday's game against Chicago,
and quoted Frye as saying, ''We weren't getting into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaughnessy had tried to talk to Everett after Friday's game,
and Everett was quoted in the story as saying, ''I have nothing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tommy Harper stepped in between the two and directed
Everett into the trainer's room, but Everett continued his
obsenity-filled verbal tirade.
</P>
<P>
   ''It became, 'Get out of here, I'll never talk to you again and
don't ever talk to me again,''' Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   Everett also yelled at Glenn Wilburn, Boston's baseball
information coordinator, and told him to get Shaughnessy out of the
clubhouse. Shaughnessy left on his own.
</P>
<P>
   The loud exchange was clearly heard in the visiting manager's
office, where Boston's Jimy Williams was holding court with
reporters, and at the same time chapel was going on in a separate
room.
</P>
</TEXT>
