<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers 4, Cubs 2  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Charlie Hayes' two-run double capped a
three-run eighth inning as the Milwaukee Brewers rallied to beat
the Chicago Cubs 4-2 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes' double off reliever Tim Worrell scored Jeromy Burnitz and
Geoff Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's much-maligned bullpen failed again and blew a strong
effort from Kerry Wood (3-6). Wood allowed six hits in 7 2-3
innings, but got into trouble in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and Milwaukee down 2-1, Ron Belliard walked and
took third on Jenkins' broken-bat single. Jenkins' bat landed 12
rows into the stands behind the Brewers' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Garibay relieved Wood, but Burnitz hit Garibay's only
pitch into left for a single, scoring Belliard with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee closer Bob Wickman, who blew a two-run lead on Friday
night, got his 11th save in 13 chances by pitching the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rodriguez, who has spent most of the year mired in a
slump, broke a 1-1 tie in the seventh inning when he hit a hanging
curveball from Milwaukee starter Jimmy Haynes into the right-field
bleachers to lead off the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes (8-7) pitched well, holding Chicago to six hits over
eight innings. He left the game trailing 2-1, but Milwaukee's rally
gave him his first victory at home since May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Before the eighth inning, the game was the second straight
pitchers' duel between two teams whose rivalry is known for its
offensive fireworks and crazy occurrences. Jeff D'Amico threw eight
innings of two-hit ball on Saturday night in Milwaukee's 4-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Milwaukee and Chicago played the longest
nine-inning game in NL history, and on Friday night, the Cubs
posted a 7-4 win in 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored Sunday's first run when Jose Nieves tripled in
the fourth inning, scoring Sammy Sosa from first base. The Cubs
could have got more when Brant Brown flied out to right, but
Burnitz, who missed making a running catch on Nieves' triple, got
Nieves at the plate with a spectacular 200-foot, no-bounce throw to
catcher Henry Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burnitz's seventh outfield assist of the year. In the
sixth inning, Jenkins also got his seventh assist by throwing out
Sosa at second base when he tried to stretch a long single into a
double.
</P>
<P>
   Wood has been inconsistent in his comeback from elbow surgery
that kept him out for all of 1999, but he was in control against
Milwaukee until losing it in the eighth. He allowed just one hit --
a first-inning double by Jenkins -- before the sixth inning in a
game filled with outstanding defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   Wood had retired 12 straight hitters before Belliard's one-out
double in the sixth. Luis Lopez doubled home Belliard to tie it at
1, but he was cut down at third on a sharp relay throw by Eric
Young.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight day, Milwaukee's largest crowd since
opening day (37,659) was in attendance. The Brewers' three-game
weekend series against their biggest rivals attracted over 100,000
fans to County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Rodriguez, who had two homers in the Cubs' series with
Milwaukee, hadn't previously driven in a run since May 27. ...
Haynes walked four batters and Wickman walked one, boosting
Milwaukee's major league-leading walk total to 409. ... After a
disastrous early season, the Cubs' starting pitchers have allowed
just 13 earned runs in Chicago's last five games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
