<DOCNO> APW20000702.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Beach Island motorists decry slower speed limit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONG BEACH TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Residents and vacationers on
Long Beach Island say the popular resort seems longer now that
speed limits on the island's main highway were reduced by 5 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The changes on Long Beach Boulevard have added time to
motorists' trips, and some residents question whether the slower
speed limits have made the road any safer.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Boulevard, which extends the length of the 18-mile
island in Ocean County, had speed limits of 35 mph and 40 mph. The
island consists of the towns of Long Beach Township, Barnegat
Light, Beach Haven, Ship Bottom, Surf City and Harvey Cedars.
</P>
<P>
   The lower speed limit took effect in May. Its chief proponent,
Long Beach Township Mayor James Mancini, said he was worried
commercial trucks would be speeding along the boulevard, a county
road. The change was approved by the county's Board of Freeholders,
of which Mancini is a member.
</P>
<P>
   But the slower speeds have made some motorists livid, especially
when they drive through parts of the island such as Loveladies,
where the road is four lanes and there are few businesses and
intersections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone is up in arms about it. Everybody's yelling about
it,'' Carolyn Rode, of High Bar Harbor section of Long Beach
Township told The Philadelphia Inquirer for Sunday's editions. ''I
don't think it's any safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rode said she was ''seething'' after a trip from Manahawkin to
her home in the northern tip of the island, which required her to
drive through Loveladies.
</P>
<P>
   Another driver found that the slower speeds merely made short
trips, well, seem longer. Barbara Wahberg said an eight-mile drive
to Beach Haven from Harvey Cedars to pick up some furniture took 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could have made it to Toms River on the (Garden State)
Parkway faster,'' she said. ''I hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beach Haven Mayor Deborah Whitcraft questioned the safety that
was to be gained by reducing the speed limits. Motorists upset with
Long Beach Boulevard speeds are likely to use the side roads that
parallel it. Those roads are often used by pedestrians to get to
the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last thing you want to do is increase traffic on the
backroads where there's so many kids going to the beach,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mancini said he was surprised by all the complaints and added he
believed there was support for the lower limit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way they talk, you'd think it went from 100 miles an hour
down to 20,'' Mancini said at a recent meeting of the town's Board
of Commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Some people do support the change, especially those who like to
ride bicycles or run along the boulevard. The road's shoulders are
narrow or nonexistent in some places.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a good idea,'' said Jennifer Emrichs, a mother of
two children. Emrichs, of Holland, Pa., said she was on vacation in
Loveladies. ''What's the hurry if you're on vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   A petition protesting the change has generated thousands of
signatures said Brian Geddes, who owns Barnegat Light Deli.
''There's so many we can't even count them. It looks like a phone
book full,'' Geddes said.
</P>
<P>
   Geddes said he teamed up with a neighboring bait shop whose
owner also has a T-shirt business.
</P>
<P>
   They have been selling T-shirts for $9 each that bear a circle
around the speed limit and a slash through it. ''The profits go
right back into more T-shirts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fuss over the speed limit has had an effect. Mancini said
the county has decided that after Oct. 1, officials would agree
with whatever speed limit island's towns want.
</P>
<P>
   ''They police it. We don't police it,'' Mancini said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-02-00 1729 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
