<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Goal and a Hug Help Hamm Rebound  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Mia Hamm's resume includes a world record
121 international goals, two World Cup titles, an Olympic gold
medal and a dynamite battle-of-the-sexes commercial with Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the player who could quit the game tomorrow with nothing
left to prove felt compelled to run to her coach on the sidelines
after scoring a goal in Saturday night's 4-1 Gold Cup semifinal
victory over Canada. Hamm hugged April Heinrichs and said, ''Thanks
for not giving up on me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an incredible scene for someone of Hamm's stature, but
her inner emotions don't always match the outer grit she shows on
the field. Heinrichs could only respond with the obvious: ''I'll
never give up on you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Mia is the sort of player that plays for the people
around her,'' Heinrichs said Sunday, a day off as the U.S. team
prepared for Monday night's championship game against Brazil. ''The
thing I'm learning about coaching her is she's not motivated by
winning. She's not intrinsically one of those people who's dying to
win every time she steps on the field. She wants to win, but what
motivates her is playing for her team and playing for her teammates
and helping them win.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Hamm plays to please others. And, lately, she
felt she hadn't been doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's 18-yard drive off the hands of Canada goalkeeper Karina
LeBlanc was her first goal against a quality opponent since March
16. Her only scores since then had come in routs of against lesser
teams such as Trinidad and Tobago when nearly the whole lineup was
scoring. Hamm went scoreless in a recent four-game Olympic tuneup
in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been struggling for a long time,'' Hamm said. ''I have
expectations to score. People have expectations for me to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Heinrichs was experimenting with younger players
almost every game. Hamm needed some positive reinforcement from the
new coach who earlier this year succeeded longtime player favorite
Tony DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hold in high regard what she thinks of us as players and as
people,'' Hamm said. ''Every meeting has been extremely positive,
and it's given me confidence to go out and play the way know I can
play. That (hug) was a kind of a token of appreciation to her and
the entire team for backing me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs was the leader and Hamm was the rising star of the
U.S. team that almost anonymously won the first World Cup in 1991.
The difference between then and now, said Heinrichs, is the
expectations. Last year's World Cup triumph attracted record
television ratings and was followed by a victory tour, a players'
strike over money, a coaching change, the announcement of a new
women's league and a quick turnaround to prepare for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we won in '91, I was on cloud nine for five or six years,
and these guys were only allowed to be on that cloud for five or
six months,'' Heinrichs said. ''Then they had to come out and start
battling again. I think, bless their hearts, they are back in it,
but one quick glimpse into what last summer was like and you wonder
how they continue to dig into that well of excitement and
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's been particularly hard on Mia, given the
pressure and the flag that she carries for this team, and the
criticism that the media had at times for her. She's fighting back.
She's starting to get her groove, and in the Gold Cup we've really
seen her come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Julie Foudy agrees, saying it's been tough dealing with
the ''lot of people tugging us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was wonderful what we did last year,'' Foudy said, ''but
the rest of the world doesn't care. And if we're going to go after
another Olympic gold medal, we need to switch gears.''
</P>
<P>
   A major step toward the gold would be a victory in the Gold Cup
title game over the Brazilians, who upset China 3-2 in Saturday's
semifinals at Louisville, Ky. The United States and Brazil tied 0-0
in group play last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, we wanted another go at them,'' Foudy said. ''I think
any time you walk away from a game like that, that's mentally,
physically exhausting, you want another chance. A 0-0 tie for us is
really a loss, so we're really looking forward to another
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada and China will play in the third-place game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
