<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Princeton Township may thin deer herd  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PRINCETON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Township officials are polishing
details of a plan that would allow hunters to kill deer at night
after Gov. Whitman signed a law suggesting state hunting rules may
be eased in areas where large herds of the animals are found.
</P>
<P>
   But animal rights activists say state lawmakers didn't have the
right to modify those rules in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The new law allows communities, airport owners and county
agriculture boards to waive some hunting rules in zones that are
overpopulated with deer.
</P>
<P>
   It changes previous rules that only allowed the state to break
its own rules, such as allowing special hunts by changing the
length of the hunting season.
</P>
<P>
   With the new law, state Department of Fish and Wildlife
officials can give permission to waive certain rules.
</P>
<P>
   Township officials said they're invoking that law and want to
launch a controlled hunt they had proposed two years ago. Under
that plan, sharpshooters would set out bait in secluded woods to
attract and shoot deer. The hunts probably would be conducted on
township property or on private farms where the owners give
permission, township officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The township began negotiating with a Connecticut company about
a year and a half ago to use trained sharpshooters in the nighttime
hunts. But state Division of Fish and Wildlife officials said using
silencers and rifles at night would violate state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Another plan would be to roundup and ship deer to a farm in
upstate New York, said township Deputy Mayor Steven Frakt. Frakt
said the township would be following the example of Millburn
Township in Essex County.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Frakt said he hopes the township will have a
program in place in time for the next winter season.
</P>
<P>
   But animal-rights activists have said they want to find a way to
shoot down the law.
</P>
<P>
   A group of animal-rights organizations last year filed a lawsuit
over the proposed special hunts. The Mercer County Deer Alliance
has said it would consider amending the lawsuit in an attempt to
invalidate the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature doesn't have the right to control something as
broad as how hunting and wildlife laws are applied in New Jersey,
said Nielsen Lewis, lawyer to the group that filed the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been our public position that this new law is legally
indefensible,'' Lewis told The Times of Trenton for Sunday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activists have said township officials should
consider alternate ways of controlling the deer herds, such as
installing roadside reflectors to keep deer away from roads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
