<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bishop Says Church Should Help Gays  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- A French bishop who was yanked from his diocese by
Pope John Paul II five years ago for challenging the Catholic
church's stand on homosexuality and priestly celibacy criticized
the Vatican on Sunday for opposing this week's Gay Pride events in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gay Pride organizers announced that the
bishop, Jacques Gaillot, would honor Vatican wishes and not
participate in a forum scheduled for Monday on religion and
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican spokesman, the Rev. Ciro Benedettini, said he was not
aware of a request to Gaillot not to participate in the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Gaillot confirmed that he had turned down the invitation to the
forum. But he expressed disappointment over the Vatican's protests
to the city of Rome to try to have the Gay Pride events canceled
because they come in the middle of Holy Year, which is drawing
millions of pilgrims to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ''The church must be where there is need, and homosexuals have
suffered innumerable discriminations,'' Gaillot said at a news
conference. ''If the church doesn't free people from oppression,
what purpose does it serve?''
</P>
<P>
   Gay Pride week began on Saturday and runs through July 8, when a
march is scheduled through Rome.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, hundreds of supporters of the extreme right held a
counter-march in the city, displaying slogans like: ''Gays at the
Colosseum? With lions inside.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The church is my home and my family,'' Gaillot said, ''but I
can't help but be critical because no one must be left out,
including homosexuals. The Holy Year is the right occasion to hold
dialogue and not to divide.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic church condemns homosexual acts but not
homosexuality itself.
</P>
<P>
   At another news conference which included Amnesty International
officials, a member of the European Parliament said that the
Vatican missed an opportunity to promote tolerance by objecting to
Gay Pride week in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, contended Lousewies van der Laan, a Europarliament
deputy from the Netherlands, ''the Catholic church is providing a
moral justification for people to promote hatred and social
exclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
