<HEADLINE> O's Johnson Copes With Trade Rumors  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Given a choice, Charles Johnson would love to
finish his career in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I enjoy playing here. I've enjoyed it from Day One,'' Johnson
said Sunday. ''I enjoy the baseball part. I enjoy the fans, they've
always treated me well since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's fate rests in the hands of Orioles owner Peter Angelos
and the rest of the team's decision-makers, none of whom appear
eager to discuss a new contract with the 28-year-old catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose contract expires after this season, is one of
several Orioles rumored to be traded before the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been hearing different things, just like everybody
else,'' he said. ''It's not a distraction at all. It's just part of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson should know. He went from the Florida Marlins to the Los
Angeles Dodgers in May 1998 trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''After my first trade, I've kind of gotten over all the trade
talk,'' he said. ''Being traded here and there, this and that.
Because I'm starting to grow up. I've learned it's part of the game
and you can't do anything bout it. A lot of times there are rumors
and you don't find out until the last minute anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no use worrying about it. I'm just trying not to let
it affect my game. I just want to go out and play the game I
love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
