<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Mass Gov. To Leave Politics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- William F. Weld once had grand political
aspirations, but those appear to be falling by the wayside and the
former Massachusetts governor said he could soon be out of politics
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Weld, a New York City lawyer in private practice with a
seven-figure salary, said just a year ago he would consider running
for president or lobbying to be the vice president in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Republican says national office no longer holds allure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have ruled out everything except a possible run for governor
of New York in 2006 and I don't think even that is very likely,''
Weld told The Boston Sunday Globe. ''I wouldn't be surprised if my
life took a completely different turn in the next five years that
would moot the 2006 New York governor's race.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld said he lives his life in five-year chunks, and the current
five-year portion will end in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a couple of years, I will have been five years at this
stint, so I expect in two or three years there will be a turn,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Weld, already a published novelist, could turn to writing full
time, he said. He is currently working on his third novel.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he may try to get into acting. He recently had a small role
in a new Steven Soderbergh crime drama, ''Traffic,'' essentially
playing himself -- a former governor and federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   His personal life, as well as his professional life, also
appears to be changing. There have been reports of problems with
his marriage. He told the Globe that his wife, Susan Roosevelt
Weld, has had a more difficult time adjusting to New York. She is
an academic specializing in ancient Chinese law who spends most of
her time in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Weld, who turns 55 on Monday, said he's working harder than he
has almost since his Harvard days as the managing partner of
McDermott Will &AMP; Emery's Manhattan office, often working 12-hour
days.
</P>
<P>
   Weld left the Massachusetts governor's office in midterm in 1997
to pursue the U.S. ambassadorship to Mexico. His appointment was
blocked by Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee. And although Weld has joked that he is
grateful to Helms for getting him out of the public eye, Weld still
has some harsh words for the North Carolina Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have come to realize that Jesse Helms stands for everything
in politics that is anathema to me,'' Weld said. ''In his position
as chairman of Foreign Relations, he does serious harm to the
national interest of the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
