<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, July 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tight Election Being Decided in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Francisco Labastida is counting on the powerful
Institutional Revolutionary Party machinery to deliver him a victory in today's
presidential election in Mexico, in the hopes that the party that has controlled
the country for 71 years will continue to do so. But Vicente Fox, a maverick
businessman, is posing a strong challenge to that wish. With voter turnout
heavy, the two men seem to be about dead even in the vote. Preliminary voter
returns aren't expected until 9:30 p.m. EDT at the earliest.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexicans In U.S. Return To Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- Despite voting rules that sharply constrain their
electoral power, Mexicans living in the United States joined caravans arranged
by political parties or headed south on their own today to vote in Mexico's
historic national elections. Mexicans with valid voting cards walked or drove to
64 special booths -- with just 750 ballots each -- in Mexico's six border
states. The booths eliminate the need for Mexicans to return to home election
districts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Engineers Blame Terrace Structure
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio (AP) -- Engineers believe the deadly collapse of a
concrete terrace at a winery on a Lake Erie island was caused by a structural
problem, not an overload of people. One person was killed and at least 75 people
were injured at the Lonz Winery when the terrace floor gave way yesterday,
dropping victims and rubble 20 feet into an old wine cellar. Police kept boaters
300 feet from the island today as tourists tried to see the damage at the
lakefront terrace of the winery's century-old main building.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Saudis Talk of Pumping More Oil
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Saudi Arabia is talking to other
producers about pumping more oil in the next few weeks in a bid to bring down
prices now at about $30 a barrel, a Saudi oil official said Sunday. The official
said the target was $25 a barrel. Saudi Arabia alone has excess production
capacity of 2.3 million barrels per day, which can be put on the market in a
short period of time if necessary, the official said. Saudi Arabia is the
world's top oil producer and exporter.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jewish Leaders: Pressure Iran on Convictions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jewish leaders in the United States called for tighter
sanctions against Iran today following the conviction of 10 Jews there on
charges of spying. ''Iran must pay a price for this,'' Rep. Eliot Engel of New
York said, joining about 150 Jewish leaders, elected officials and protesters
gathered outside the Iranian Mission to the United Nations. Engel and New York
congressmen Anthony Weiner and Major Owens pledged to work to reinstate the
trade bans and withdraw other forms of import and agricultural assistance to
Iran.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright Christens Navy Missile
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATH, Maine (AP) -- A guided-missile destroyer named for the Navy's all-time
''ace of aces'' was christened today by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at
its launching today at Bath Iron Works. The McCampbell, the 20th Arleigh
Burke-class Aegis destroyer built at the shipyard, was named in honor of Navy
Capt. David McCampbell, a Medal of Honor winner who was credited with shooting
down 34 Japanese planes during World War II.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mongolia Opposition Claims Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) -- The ex-communist opposition claimed a crushing
victory Monday against Mongolia's ruling party in the weekend's parliamentary
elections, even though official results were not yet in. Such a victory for the
Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party would be a stunning political reversal in
the remote Asian nation, which dealt the former communists an overwhelming
defeat in 1996 elections.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Irwin Wins Senior Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Hale Irwin overcame a two-stroke deficit with a
6-under-par 65 to win his second U.S. Senior Open in three years. He finished
with a 17-under 267 today, the lowest total in tournament history, surpassing
Gary Player's 270 in 1987. Bruce Fleisher, who had led after the first three
rounds, shot a 70 and finished at 270. He was seeking his 11th senior victory in
two years. ''Statements are made and statements are forgotten,'' Irwin said when
asked if he was trying to prove that he was the best player among the seniors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubs' Sosa Wants Contract Extension
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- With trade rumors still swirling and his agents' talks with
the Chicago Cubs apparently going nowhere, it appears Sammy Sosa just wants
someone to want him. Sosa took a little extra time stripping off his uniform in
the cramped visitors' clubhouse at County Stadium today, and his famous smile
was nowhere to be seen. He didn't speak to reporters after the Cubs blew a
one-run lead in the eighth inning of their 4-2 loss to the Brewers. The weight
of trade rumors and a slump at the plate are taking their toll on Sosa.
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS 
</P>
</TEXT>
