<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aftershocks Continue in Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Strong aftershocks were likely to continue for a
week on Japanese islands jolted by a powerful quake that killed one
man, buckled roads and demolished a shrine, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people living near a cliff on Kozushima island were
evacuated as more than a thousand aftershocks were recorded since
Saturday's magnitude 6.4 quake, said island official Hiroyoshi
Shimizu.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 200 residents on the island took shelter overnight at a
public facility or at relatives' homes, another island official,
Tomihiro Ishinoda, said Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroyoshi said the quake destroyed roads at six places and
damaged more than 10 houses and 100 gravestones on Kozushima, 95
miles south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The main building of a shrine was crushed under a landslide, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shimizu said about 50 Self-Defense Force soldiers left the
island Sunday after removing boulders that had tumbled from
mountainsides and clearing roads of debris.
</P>
<P>
   A 5.4-magnitude quake jolted the island at 5:03 a.m. Monday and
was centered at a depth about 6 miles under the seabed near the
island, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's earthquake center said magnitude 4.5 and 4.9
aftershocks were registered Sunday and predicted that fairly strong
quakes would continue to shake the island.
</P>
<P>
   It warned residents to be on the alert for four or five days.
</P>
<P>
   The quake Saturday afternoon struck the Izu islands with the
biggest force on Niijima and Kozushima, an island of about 2,300
people.
</P>
<P>
   A 34-year-old motorist was buried under falling rocks on
Kozushima and died at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   It also shook Miyakejima, just southeast of Kozushima, where
residents were allowed to return to their homes on Friday after
fears of a volcanic eruption subsided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
