<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State reopens Interstate rest stops between Albany, Plattsburgh  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state will rebuild and reopen rest areas
along the Northway starting with a $17.2 million project this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   That project funded with state and federal money will tear down
and replace an old rest stop between exits 29 and 30 near North
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 14 rest stops along Interstate 87 between Albany and
the Canadian border have been closed since 1991. Officials said the
decision as made to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Transportation's long-range plans call
for 12 rest areas within two years, including the renovation of
stops in Schroon Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ''Especially at night and during the long winters, you'll feel a
lot more comfortable stopping at some of those rest areas,'' said
Thomas Bergin, spokesman for state Sen. Ronald Stafford,
R-Plattsburgh. ''I've been up there plenty of times in February at
10 or 11 o'clock at night, and it's like you're on another
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   New rest areas will include space for state police and the U.S.
Border Patrol. There won't be restaurants or gift shops.
</P>
<P>
   The design will reflect old Adirondack Great Camps. Exteriors
are proposed to be wavy wood siding stained a dark earth tone with
a dark green asphalt shingle roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
