<HEADLINE> Fan arrested after throwing ball on John Rocker  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Brooklyn man was charged with reckless
endangerment after throwing a baseball at Atlanta Braves' pitcher
John Rocker during the New York Mets' game Sunday afternoon at Shea
Stadium, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Sweeney, 25, was arrested around 3:30 p.m. when police
say he threw a ball at Rocker after the Braves reliever tossed it
into the stands. Rocker had been warming up with outfielder Reggie
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's presence this weekend brought out about 700 police
officers and created a media circus to Shea. He has repeatedly
enflamed New Yorkers' emotions with derogatory comments about the
city.
</P>
<P>
   In other trouble surrounding the last of the Mets four-game
series with the Braves, police issued 272 summonses for people with
open beer containers and charged 64 people with ticket scalping.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta won Sunday 10-2, leaving the series evenly split with
the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
