Albright Christens Navy Missile
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATH, Maine (AP) -- A guided-missile destroyer named for the Navy's all-time
''ace of aces'' was christened today by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at
its launching today at Bath Iron Works. The McCampbell, the 20th Arleigh
Burke-class Aegis destroyer built at the shipyard, was named in honor of Navy
Capt. David McCampbell, a Medal of Honor winner who was credited with shooting
down 34 Japanese planes during World War II.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DotComGuy Passes Halfway Mark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- DotComGuy, a 26-year-old computer systems manager, who rented
a Dallas town house six months ago and volunteered to live off e-commerce for a
year, has passed the halfway mark without losing it. The effort has corporate
sponsorship from online interests that hope DotComGuy's life -- and its
dependence on the Internet -- will encourage others to use cyberspace for
transactions normally reserved for the storefront. Two dozen cameras provide
video of DotComGuy's almost every move. His only sanctuary from the cameras is a
bathroom.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Armstrong in Second at Tour
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUDUN, France (AP) -- Defending champion Lance Armstrong remained in second
place in the Tour de France despite finishing way back in Sunday's first road
stage. Tom Steels of Belgium won the close stage, finishing the mostly flat
120-mile course from Futuroscope to Loudun in 4 hours, 46 minutes, 8 seconds.
Steels edged Australia's Stuart O'Grady in a frantic sprint to the finish line
but Britain's David Millar retained the yellow jersey as the overall leader and
stretched his advantage over Armstrong to four seconds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockies Nip Padres 3-2 in 10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Woody Williams pitched eight strong innings in his first
start following surgery for an aneurysm, but the Colorado Rockies scored an
unearned run in the 10th inning to beat the San Diego Padres 3-2 today. Jeff
Cirillo's second sacrifice fly of the game, off closer Trevor Hoffman (1-3),
scored Mike Lansing, who had reached with one out on second baseman Bret Boone's
fielding error and third on Todd Helton's single.
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS 
</P>
