<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Girl, embarrassed by school's tattered flag, gets one flown over Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) - Ten-year-old tiffany Small was upset that
the flag flying in front of her elementary school was tattered and
faded.
</P>
<P>
   So she did something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hated seeing that old flag,'' she said. ''It is very rude to
fly a flag that is like that ... We need to respect our country. I
wanted to show how much we really cared for our flag. If a soldier
came by and they saw our flag the way it was, he would have thought
that our school wouldn't care about our country. That would be very
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The student enlisted her teacher and a friend and wrote letters
to get a new flag for the Genesee School, 23 miles west of
Syracuse. She recently ended up with a beauty, one that was flown
over the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   She celebrates July 4th for the freedom it represents.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday is ''something that would make us think about our
country and (try) not to be as cruel as everybody is in our world
today. We need to stop teasing and all the things that people do.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I like our freedoms.'' she told The Citizen of Auburn.
''That's why we had all of these wars, so we could have freedom.
The freedom I like best is happiness. I like going out and shopping
with my friends, having fun, doing yard work and playing with my
dogs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
