<HEADLINE> Sunday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Air Canada To Prolong Contract Talks
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Air Canada and its pilots agreed Sunday to
prolong their contract talks, giving travelers at least a few more
days of worry-free flying.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not given strike notice at this time,'' Peter Foster,
a spokesman for the Air Canada Pilot's Association, said in an
interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fair to say there's enough happening at the table to
warrant the continuation of talks.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood among Air Canada negotiators was equally optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been considerable progress made during the past four
days of negotiations and we remain firmly focused on negotiating a
settlement without disruption to our customers,'' said Calin
Rovinescu, an executive with Corporate Development Strategy, the
company leading the talks for the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots have been in a legal strike position since June 26,
when the union announced its members had voted 95 per cent in favor
of a strike mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The main issues for the union, which represents 2,200 pilots,
are wages, pensions, working conditions and job security.
------
Labrador Helicopter Back in Service
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- A Labrador helicopter that was
grounded Saturday was fixed and back in service Sunday in the
search for a missing home-built airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The Labrador is part of the hunt for a Pelican Cub airplane with
two 43-year-old men aboard. It was to join another Labrador on
Sunday evening to search for the tiny airplane in an area of about
6,000 square kilometers
</P>
<P>
   The airplane disappeared over the southern tip of Baffin Island
in Nunavut on Thursday, after leaving the community of Lake Harbor
on a one-hour flight north to the territorial capital Iqaluit.
</P>
<P>
   The search also includes two Hercules airplanes, two bush planes
and a small Coast Guard helicopter.
------
Motorhome Plows Into Crowd, Injures Seven
</P>
<P>
   OSOYOOS, British Columbia (AP) -- Canada Day celebrations turned
chaotic when a motorhome plowed into a crowd of people, injuring
seven, at least one seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the motorhome lost control and struck two parked
cars and a motorcycle before plunging into the crowd, Sgt. Ted
Cronmiller said. He said was wasn't clear what caused the driver to
lose control.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands were celebrating the July 1 holiday Saturday at the
annual Osoyoos Cherry Fiesta in Osoyoos, British Columbia, about
260 kilometers east of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person who suffered a head injury was flown to
hospital in Kelowna, British Columbia The others were taken to
hospitals in nearby Oliver and Penticton, B.C, MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest victim was an eight-year-old girl, who suffered a
broken wrist. Several others had minor cuts and bruises.
------
</P>
<P>
   Balanced Budgets Too Late for NDP
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- British Columbia's attempt to
put the brakes on a decade of red ink by introducing a
balanced-budget law won't be the political salvation of the NDP,
says a University of Victoria political expert.
</P>
<P>
   ''My sense, in talking to people, is the die has been cast,''
says Michael Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fudge-it budgets are still lingering in people's minds.
This isn't going to be a magic wand to save them politically.''
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Premier Ujjal Dosanjh said his government's
law, introduced last week, will help restore NDP credibility and
show he means business when he says he wants to get a handle on the
province's finances.
</P>
<P>
   There have been nine consecutive deficits and a doubling of the
provincial debt to $36 billion under the NDP government.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the 1996 provincial election, the NDP tabled what it
said were two surplus budgets. But shortly after being re-elected,
the government said the economy had worsened and the budgets were
in the red, touching off what became known as the fudge-it budget
scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
