<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS to restore dropped AP logo  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy dropped
anchor Sunday near the Statue of Liberty, where it will serve as
centerpiece for New York's nautical Fourth of July extravaganza of
warships, tall ships and thousands of private watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   With the party just two days away, there were other foretellings
of the massive influx of vessels expected to jam the harbor from
Brooklyn to New Jersey and Verazzano to Manhattan. The U.S. Coast
Guard has estimated as many as 70,000 small craft might show up.
</P>
<P>
   Some 150 sailing ships from 23 countries and 25 naval ships from
14 nations will take part in the dual event - Operation Sail 2000
and an International Naval Review, the sixth in just over a
century. In numbers at least, the naval review appeared to be
falling short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, skies over the harbor were abuzz with military
helicopters, and small groups of white-uniformed sailors on shore
leave were the vanguard of an expected throng of some 28,000
seafarers for the weeklong celebration. Some 3,000 to 4,000 small
craft already were at moorings in the harbor and shore marinas,
Coast Guard officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tempo is picking up,'' said U.S. Navy Capt. Woody Berzins,
a spokesman for the INR. ''This is the culmination of the things
we've been planning for more than two years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question that this will be the largest assemblage
ever of tall ships and naval vessels,'' said Greg Perrin, vice
president of OpSail 2000. As for the spectator fleet, he said
experience shows that many arrive just before the event, and
''within hours, there's no water any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Warrant Officer Lionel Bryant said the service was
standing by its estimate of 40,000 to 70,000 spectator craft for
the July 4 event, ''depending on the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   As for security and other preparations, ''we're on target of
where we wanted to be,'' Bryant said. ''If we can just get the
weather and the cooperation of everyone, this should go off without
a hitch.''
</P>
<P>
   While the stately sailing ships are the main attraction, Navy
officials originally had planned for history's largest naval
review, with 61 nations invited to take part. That was scaled back
to a more modest 50 entries, but the event appeared to be falling
well short of any chance to break the record of 25 navies
represented at the 1986 Statue of Liberty centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official list given out to news organizations said
36 ships would take part in the review, a list provided by Berzins
showed only 25 - 10 from the United States, two from Canada and two
from Japan, plus one each from Ireland, Britain, Ukraine, India,
Greece, France, Italy, Brazil, South Africa, Singapore and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Navy spokesmen said they couldn't explain the discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   While many ships will be visiting Gotham for the first time, the
Norfolk, Va.-based Kennedy is no stranger. Commissioned in 1968 as
the Navy's last conventionally powered carrier, it has participated
in the city's annual ''Fleet Week'' festivities for a decade. The
Navy's eight newer, nuclear-powered carriers are not allowed in New
York harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The JFK, 80,000 tons and 1,052 feet long, anchored at midday
just south of the Statue of Liberty, near the amphibious assault
ship USS Nassau, a helicopter carrier that arrived on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, President Clinton will inspect the 11-mile line of
warships in the Hudson River from aboard the missile cruiser USS
Hue City, then transfer by Coast Guard cutter to the JFK, where he
will view the ''parade of sail'' from the flight deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Hue City, one of the Navy's powerful, billion-dollar
Aegis-type cruisers, steamed up the harbor late Sunday, bound for a
Hudson River pier near the Intrepid, a famed World war II carrier
turned military museum. The Hue City is the only U.S. Navy ship
named for a Vietnam war battle.
</P>
<P>
   The all-day harbor activities will be capped at night by what
organizers call the largest fireworks display ever: some 60 tons of
explosives launched from barges at five locations, capped by a
grand finale blast near the Statue of Liberty. Organizers say as
many as four million people may see some part of the day aboard
watercraft or from vantage points in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to naval ships, the official U.S. contingent will
include two Coast Guard cutters and the oceanographic vessel Rude,
famous for its undersea scanning achievements that included
locating the crash sites of TWA 800 and John F. Kennedy's private
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Rude, owned by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration (NOAA), also surveyed the bottom of New York harbor
last year as part of the preparations for OpSail 2000, and located
six previously unknown shipwrecks, said NOAA spokeswoman Connie
Barclay.
</P>
<P>
   Other vessels were gathering in waters outside the Narrows in
preparation for their entry into the harbor. A Canadian warship was
to lead the naval contingent into the harbor before noon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The naval craft will form a line at anchor 11 miles long in the
Hudson River, south of the George Washington Bridge. The sailing
ships are to parade up the Hudson, then turn and disperse to
various preassigned piers and moorings, for public visits through
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
