<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Party Fights for Capital  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A left-of-center candidate appeared headed
for victory in Mexico City's mayoral race, while two center-right
candidates were leading in two key governorships, according to exit
polls released late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll for the Televisa network showed center-left
Democratic Revolution Party candidate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador
ahead in the Mexico City mayor's race. The poll said he had 40
percent compared with 34 percent for Santiago Creel of the
center-right National Action Party and 22 percent for Jesus Silva
Herzog of the nationally ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party,
or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Another exit poll, done for the TV Azteca network, had Lopez
Obrador with 34 percent to Creel's 31 percent and Silva Herzog's 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Morelos, just south of the capital, National
Action's Sergio Estrada captured the governorship from the PRI by
57 percent to 29 percent for the PRI's Juan Salgado Brito,
according to the Televisa poll. TV Azteca had it 47-22 for National
Action.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa's poll said National Action was holding presidential
candidate Vicente Fox's home state of Guanajuato with 57 percent
for Juan Carlos Romero Hicks to 33 percent for the PRI's Juan
Ignacio Torres Landa in the governor's race. TV Azteca had the race
at 50-25.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa's poll had a 1 percentage point margin of error, while
TV Azteca's margin of error was 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised statement, National Action's national
president, Luis Felipe Bravo Mena, declared victory in Morelos and
Guanajuato.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Revolution Party almost swept the board in 1997,
when Mexico City held its first mayor's race in decades, replacing
a presidentially appointed mayor with an elected one.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the party's presidential candidate this
year, won a stunning victory and his party crushed the opposition
in races for local and federal legislators in chaotic Mexico City,
North America's largest metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the party has won three other governorships and is
part of an alliance in another state. But Cardenas was trailing in
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Obrador is a former PRI state leader who lost a 1994
election in Tabasco. State electoral officials, most close to the
PRI, rejected complaints of massive overspending by the PRI. The
federal attorney general's office said there was strong evidence of
election violations, but said it had no jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   After that vote, Lopez Obrador moved to Mexico City and became
national president of Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time Sunday, Mexico City residents also elected
the presidents of the city's 16 boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls had shown that while Lopez Obrador led in the
mayoral contest, Fox was leading in presidential polls in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
