<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanford Fire Crews Sent Home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Workers at the Hanford nuclear
reservation were allowed to return Sunday, following a 191,000-acre
fire that disrupted thousands of lives and raised fears about
possible radiation releases.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of firefighters drafted from around the
region had returned home, leaving a few local firefighters to
ensure hot spots would not flare up.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford managers, who had barred all but a few essential workers
from the site during the crisis, said Sunday that all employees
could return. On Monday, most of the site's 10,000 workers will
resume the task of cleaning up nuclear waste at Hanford, which
contains the nation's largest volume of such wastes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the return-to-work directive was issued, a team examined
all Hanford buildings to check for damage and ensure telephone
networks and power systems were operating, said Erik Olds, a U.S.
Department of Energy spokesman at Hanford. No major problems were
found.
</P>
<P>
   Air sampling conducted by the Energy Department and the state
Department of Health has indicated no radiation releases occurred
as a result of the fire. Further test results from the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency are pending.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, started Tuesday by a fatal traffic accident, destroyed
20 homes and scores of other buildings just south of the Hanford
border. One man suffered serious burns.
</P>
<P>
   At the fire's peak late Wednesday, about 7,000 people were
evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 2257 </TRAILER>
