<DOCNO> APW20000702.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Opposition Party Sees Chance  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- It has been a long, hard wait for Mexico's
largest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing its activists ignored, jailed, or derided as
anti-patriotic for generations, the National Action Party on Sunday
was apparently on the verge of electoral triumph behind its
presidential candidate, Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   National Action -- known by its Spanish acronym PAN -- was founded
in 1939 under Manuel Gomez Morin, a leading Mexican intellectual
who opposed the big-government trends of the ruling party at that
era.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the party appealed to religious, middle-class
Mexicans frustrated by the single-party domination of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and to what were then
tough restrictions on the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling PRI of that era allowed other parties -- but not real
opposition. It used fraud and violence to crush foes at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   National Action was long associated in the popular mind with
Catholic lay groups -- stifling its development among other sectors
opposed to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Even this year, critics on the left accused it of of
''fascism,'' a reference to the conservative social views held by
many of its leaders and to a minor thread within the party that
dates back to the pro-fascist Sinarquista movement of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   But the PAN has always worked peacefully through the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   And since the 1970s, it has increasingly become a party of
Mexico's growing urban middle classes and business sectors who were
less interested in the church than in a cleaner, smaller
government.
</P>
<P>
   The party's candidate this year, pragmatic businessman Vicente
Fox, has tried to broaden the party's base further, promising to
embrace even some leftist policies in efforts to make the party the
center of efforts to topple the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the late 1940s did National Action party manage to
elect its first few congressmen, after a legal battle. Not until
1952 did it bother even trying to seek the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1961, it only ran for about half of the congressional
seats on offer. By the 1970s, it was winning more than 20 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alvarez, National Action's presidential candidate in 1958,
recalls seeing his campaign workers -- even himself -- jailed during
the campaign and some physically attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some hotels refused to give us a room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The party finished third in the crucial 1988 election. Many
thought the PRI stole the election from a leftist coalition headed
by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking legitimacy, then-President Carlos Salinas forged a
tactical alliance with the PAN -- under Alvarez -- which pushed him
into a series of major political reforms that significantly opened
the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the PAN won its first governorship. On Sunday, it won
its sixth state governorship, in Morelos, and it is part of a
coalition in another. Entering Sunday, the PAN also governed eight
of Mexico's 10 largest cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-02-00 2258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000702.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, July 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Opposition Candidate Leads in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Four national exit polls are giving an edge to opposition
candidate Vicente Fox in historic presidential elections today that could bring
an end to the ruling party's 71-year lock on the presidency. A Fox victory would
be almost unthinkable for many in Mexico, where the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is almost synonymous with the government -- and
even the nation itself -- to millions of supporters and detractors alike. One
poll showed Fox, of the conservative National Action Party, with 44 percent, the
PRI's Francisco Labastida with 38 percent and leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas with
16 percent of the vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Engineers Blame Terrace Structure
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio (AP) -- Engineers believe the deadly collapse of a
concrete terrace at a winery on a Lake Erie island was caused by a structural
problem, not an overload of people. One person was killed and at least 75 people
were injured at the Lonz Winery when the terrace floor gave way yesterday,
dropping victims and rubble 20 feet into an old wine cellar. Police kept boaters
300 feet from the island today as tourists tried to see the damage at the
lakefront terrace of the winery's century-old main building.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Would Mull Suspending Gas Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House would likely go along if the Senate votes to
suspend the 18-cent federal gas tax, but a new way would have to be found to pay
for highway construction, the House majority leader says. At any rate, Rep. Dick
Armey said, suspending the tax would be a temporary fix to a permanent problem
of high gasoline prices. More helpful would be to augment the natural gas
delivery system, deal more forcefully with foreign oil suppliers and cut down on
oil imports, he said on ''Fox News Sunday.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Schools Seek More Male Teachers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- At a time when recruiting qualified teachers is a
challenge for school districts nationwide, trying to find men to teach in
elementary school is proving to be particularly difficult. Across California,
for instance, just 14 percent of the roughly 159,000 public elementary school
teachers are men, equal to the national average. Educators say reasons vary for
the absence of male teachers in elementary grades. Among them: Men often find it
easier to relate to older students.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
March Planned by N. Ireland Protestants
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Signaling a potentially violent week
ahead, leaders of Northern Ireland's major Protestant group vowed Sunday to
march past Roman Catholic homes in this bitterly polarized town. More than 2,000
members and supporters of the Orange Order marched to Drumcree, an Anglican
church near Portadown, where British security forces for the past two years have
prevented the Protestant group from parading past a nearby Catholic
neighborhood.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mongolia Opposition Claims Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) -- The ex-communist opposition claimed a crushing
victory Monday against members of Mongolia's former coalition government in
weekend parliamentary elections, even though official results were not yet in.
Such a victory for the Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party would be a
stunning political reversal in the remote Asian nation, which dealt the former
communists an overwhelming defeat in 1996 elections. The party said it had
clinched 69 seats in the 76-member legislature.
</P>
