<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks for Help with Myanmar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAN MAE LA, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand has asked the international
community to hold talks on repatriating more than 100,000 refugees
who have fled military rule in neighboring Myanmar, reports said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The call was made on Sunday as Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
toured the largest refugee camp along the Myanmar-Thai border,
accompanied by senior Thai officials and U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees representative Jahanshah Assadi.
</P>
<P>
   Some human rights groups have criticized Thailand for deporting
some of the refugees to Myanmar, also known as Burma, where human
rights abuses have been widely reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuan told reporters that the refugees would be allowed to
remain on Thai soil as long as the situation remained unsafe for
them in Myanmar. However, he said migrant workers would be
repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier the Thai government said it intended to send back all
refugees within three years, but Chuan said ''maybe it will take
more time, three to five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuan called for more help, particularly from the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, in pressing for negotiations with
Myanmar on returning the refugees, who come mostly from the
country's minority ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Their temporary refuge on Thai soil is a burden on civilians and
military, and is at the expense of the environment and security, he
said, as he met with some of the camp's nearly 31,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-based group Human Rights Watch has over the past two
months denounced the Thai government for forcibly repatriating more
than 100 Karen refugees and urged it to provide more protection for
those remaining on its soil.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand toughened its policy after a raid on the Myanmar
embassy in Bangkok last October by student radicals opposed to the
Myanmar regime, and a hostage-taking in January by the rebel God's
Army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
